INSERT INTO `documents` VALUES (24,'EHS-001','EHS-001 Permit to work Procedure','Permit to work procedure SOP','tcpdf/2025 EHS En KPI Sep.pdf',29,2,'2025-09-26 09:17:09',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(25,'EHS-003','EHS-003 Environmental Aspects and Impacts','Environmental Aspects and Impacts SOP','tcpdf/2025 EHS En KPI Sep.pdf',29,2,'2025-09-26 09:17:09',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,1,3,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(26,'EHS-004','EHS-004 Audit Procedure','Audit procedure SOP','tcpdf/2025 EHS En KPI Sep.pdf',29,2,'2025-09-26 09:17:09',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(27,'EHS-005A','EHS-005 Chemical Substance Management','Chemical Substance Management SOP','tcpdf/2025 EHS En KPI Sep.pdf',29,2,'2025-09-26 09:17:09',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(28,'EHS-006B','EHS-006B Environmental Health and Safety Objectives and Targets','Objectives and targets SOP','tcpdf/2025 EHS En KPI Sep.pdf',29,2,'2025-09-26 09:17:09',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(29,'EHS-007A','EHS-007A Environmental Health & Safety Communication & Compliant Procedure','Communication & Complaint procedure SOP','tcpdf/2025 EHS En KPI Sep.pdf',29,2,'2025-09-26 09:17:09',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(30,'EHS-008C','EHS-008C EHS Management Review','Management review SOP','tcpdf/2025 EHS En KPI Sep.pdf',29,2,'2025-09-26 09:17:09',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(31,'EHS-009B','EHS-009B Preparation and Control of EHS SOP\'s','Preparation and control SOP','tcpdf/2025 EHS En KPI Sep.pdf',29,2,'2025-09-26 09:17:09',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(32,'EHS-010B','EHS-010B EHS Record Retention Policy','Record retention policy SOP','tcpdf/2025 EHS En KPI Sep.pdf',29,2,'2025-09-26 09:17:09',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(33,'EHS-000','Safety Statement 2024 Rev 8','Safety Statement for Amneal Ireland','tcpdf/2025 EHS En KPI Sep.pdf',29,2,'2025-09-26 09:17:09','2025-12-02',NULL,NULL,1,1,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(41,'EHS-004E','Environmental, Health & Safety & Energy Audit & Inspection Procedure','To verify compliance with Environment, Health, Safety, and Energy Policies, Procedures, and Legislation. To determine the effectiveness of the EHS and Energy management systems.\n---\nCovers the elements of the EHS and Energy Management Systems and the requirements of ISO14001:2015, ISO45001:2018, and ISO50001:2018.\n---\nThis procedure verifies compliance with EHS and Energy Policies, Procedures, and Legislation. It determines the effectiveness of the EHS and Energy management systems.\n---\n- EHS-004: First Issued.\n- EHS-004A: Editorial changes to include ISO14001:2015 requirements.\n- EHS-004B: Updated to include Energy policy.\n- EHS-004C: Updated to include ISO45001:2018 and ISO50001:2018.\n- EHS-004D: Definitions added for Operational Audit and SME.\n- EHS-004E: Updated to remove reference to Action Management Software.\n---\n- EHS and Facilities: Implementation and maintenance of the EHS and Energy procedure.\n- Internal Audit Team: Carry out system audits.\n- Management Group: Ensure corrective actions are completed on time.','EHS-004 Audit Procedure.pdf',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:01:48',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'To verify compliance with Environment, Health, Safety, and Energy Policies, Procedures, and Legislation. To determine the effectiveness of the EHS and Energy management systems.','Covers the elements of the EHS and Energy Management Systems and the requirements of ISO14001:2015, ISO45001:2018, and ISO50001:2018.','This procedure verifies compliance with EHS and Energy Policies, Procedures, and Legislation. It determines the effectiveness of the EHS and Energy management systems.','- Amneal Ireland: Amneal Ireland Limited, Cahir Road, Cashel, Co. Tipperary, Ireland.\n- Systems Audit: Detailed examination of processes, conditions, or systems related to ISO14001, ISO45001, and ISO50001.\n- Operational Audit: Detailed examination of SEUs (Significant Energy Users).\n- EHS: Environmental, Health, and Safety.\n- CAPA: Corrective Action Preventative Action.','- EHS and Facilities: Implementation and maintenance of the EHS and Energy procedure.\n- Internal Audit Team: Carry out system audits.\n- Management Group: Ensure corrective actions are completed on time.','- EHS-004: First Issued.\n- EHS-004A: Editorial changes to include ISO14001:2015 requirements.\n- EHS-004B: Updated to include Energy policy.\n- EHS-004C: Updated to include ISO45001:2018 and ISO50001:2018.\n- EHS-004D: Definitions added for Operational Audit and SME.\n- EHS-004E: Updated to remove reference to Action Management Software.','EHS-004D','- FM-EHS-010: Area Inspection Checklist.\n- FM-EHS-011: Internal EHS Audit Report.\n- FM-EHS-012: SEU Energy Operational Audit Checklist.'),(42,'EHS-001A','Permit to Work','To ensure safe execution of critical tasks through a permit-to-work system, minimizing risks and ensuring compliance with safety standards.\n---\nApplies to all critical tasks requiring permits, including confined space entry, hot work, working at height, and electrical work.\n---\n- Defines the permit-to-work system for safe execution of critical tasks.\n- Covers tasks like confined space entry, hot work, working at height, and electrical work.\n- Requires risk assessments, method statements, and approvals before work begins.\n---\n- **Revision 0**: First Issued.\n- **Revision A (07-Jul-2021)**: Updated template, form references, and permit validity to 7 days.\n---\n- **Permit User**: Completes risk assessments, ensures safe work execution.\n- **Permit Approver**: Reviews and approves permits.\n- **Area Owner**: Coordinates work activities and ensures safety.\n- **EHS Engineer**: Audits the permit-to-work system.','EHS-001 Permit to Work Procedure.pdf',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:01:48',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'To ensure safe execution of critical tasks through a permit-to-work system, minimizing risks and ensuring compliance with safety standards.','Applies to all critical tasks requiring permits, including confined space entry, hot work, working at height, and electrical work.','- Defines the permit-to-work system for safe execution of critical tasks.\n- Covers tasks like confined space entry, hot work, working at height, and electrical work.\n- Requires risk assessments, method statements, and approvals before work begins.','- **Permit Approver**: Individual authorized to approve permits.\n- **Permit User**: Competent person supervising the work.\n- **Hot Work**: Work producing sparks, flames, or ignition sources.\n- **Lock Out/Tag Out**: Procedures to isolate energy sources.\n- **Critical Safe Work**: Tasks like confined space entry, hot work, and working at height.','- **Permit User**: Completes risk assessments, ensures safe work execution.\n- **Permit Approver**: Reviews and approves permits.\n- **Area Owner**: Coordinates work activities and ensures safety.\n- **EHS Engineer**: Audits the permit-to-work system.','- **Revision 0**: First Issued.\n- **Revision A (07-Jul-2021)**: Updated template, form references, and permit validity to 7 days.',NULL,'- EHS-001.F01-00: Confined Space Permit to Work.\n- EHS-001.F02-00: Hot Work Permit.\n- EHS-001.F03-00: Working at Heights Permit.\n- EHS-001.F04-00: General Work Permit.\n- EHS-001.F05-00: Line Breaking & Isolation Permit.\n- EHS-001.F06-00: Energised Electrical Work Permit.\n- EHS-001.F07-00: Excavating and Trenching Permit.\n- EHS-001.F08-00: Crane Operations Permit.'),(43,'EHS-011A','Identification & Review of Environment, Health & Safety Legislative and Other Requirements','To identify and review relevant Irish and EU legislation, planning permissions, permits, and licenses to ensure compliance with EHS requirements.\n---\nApplies to all EHS legislative and regulatory requirements relevant to Amneal Ireland, including planning permissions, permits, and licenses.\n---\n- Identifies and reviews relevant Irish and EU legislation.\n- Maintains a legal register for compliance.\n- Ensures compliance with planning permissions, permits, and licenses.\n- Conducts annual reviews of EHS legislative compliance.\n---\n- **EHS-011**: First Issued.\n- **EHS-011A (17-Apr-19)**: Changed \"EHS Manager\" to \"EHS Department.\"\n---\n- **EHS Department**: Responsible for maintaining the EHS Legal Register, reviewing changes, and ensuring compliance.\n- **Antaris**: Assists in the annual review of legislative requirements.','EHS-011 EHS Legislative.pdf',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:01:48',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'To identify and review relevant Irish and EU legislation, planning permissions, permits, and licenses to ensure compliance with EHS requirements.','Applies to all EHS legislative and regulatory requirements relevant to Amneal Ireland, including planning permissions, permits, and licenses.','- Identifies and reviews relevant Irish and EU legislation.\n- Maintains a legal register for compliance.\n- Ensures compliance with planning permissions, permits, and licenses.\n- Conducts annual reviews of EHS legislative compliance.',NULL,'- **EHS Department**: Responsible for maintaining the EHS Legal Register, reviewing changes, and ensuring compliance.\n- **Antaris**: Assists in the annual review of legislative requirements.','- **EHS-011**: First Issued.\n- **EHS-011A (17-Apr-19)**: Changed \"EHS Manager\" to \"EHS Department.\"','EHS-011','- Pegasus Legal Register (WWW.PegasusLegalRegister.com)'),(44,'EHS-012','Chemical Risk Assessment','To assess risks associated with hazardous chemicals, communicate these risks to employees, and establish a program for periodic exposure monitoring.\n---\nApplies to the use of hazardous chemicals at the Amneal Ireland facility.\n---\n- Describes the procedure for risk assessment of hazardous chemicals.\n- Communicates chemical risks to employees.\n- Establishes a program for periodic employee exposure monitoring.\n---\n- **EHS-012**: First Issued.\n---\n- **Site Leader**: Designates a qualified person to coordinate chemical risk assessments and exposure monitoring.\n- **EHS Specialist**: Ensures risk assessments are carried out for existing and new hazardous chemicals.','EHS-012 Chemical Risk Assessment.pdf',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:01:48',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'To assess risks associated with hazardous chemicals, communicate these risks to employees, and establish a program for periodic exposure monitoring.','Applies to the use of hazardous chemicals at the Amneal Ireland facility.','- Describes the procedure for risk assessment of hazardous chemicals.\n- Communicates chemical risks to employees.\n- Establishes a program for periodic employee exposure monitoring.','- **EHS Specialist**: A trained person knowledgeable about chemical properties and health effects.\n- **Site Leader**: Person responsible for EHS on site.\n- **Hazardous Chemical**: Any chemical that can cause harm.\n- **Exposure**: Contact with chemicals through skin, inhalation, ingestion, or injection.\n- **OELV (Occupational Exposure Limit Value)**: Air concentration limits for safe exposure.','- **Site Leader**: Designates a qualified person to coordinate chemical risk assessments and exposure monitoring.\n- **EHS Specialist**: Ensures risk assessments are carried out for existing and new hazardous chemicals.','- **EHS-012**: First Issued.','N/A','- EHS-005 Chemical Substance Management.\n- ES-009 Risk Management.\n- FM-EHS-011-00 Chemical Risk Assessment form.\n- Chemical Agent Code of Practice 2016.'),(45,'EHS-013','Use of Amneal Ireland Company Vehicles','To establish procedures for the safe use of Amneal Ireland\'s owned or leased vehicles, ensuring compliance with local regulations and safe driving practices.\n---\nApplies to the operation of Amneal Ireland owned or leased vehicles on public roadways, private property, and Amneal property. Excludes specialized off-road equipment like forklifts.\n---\n- Establishes procedures for the use of Amneal Ireland\'s owned or leased vehicles.\n- Ensures safe operation on public roadways, private property, and Amneal property.\n- Requires drivers to maintain valid licenses and report incidents promptly.\n---\n- **EHS-013**: First Issued.\n---\n- **Authorised Drivers**: Maintain valid licenses, report incidents, and comply with local regulations.\n- **Department Management**: Qualify and authorise employees for vehicle operation.\n- **EHS Department**: Establish safe operation procedures and investigate incidents.\n- **Maintenance Department**: Ensure vehicles are roadworthy.\n- **Finance Department**: Manage vehicle procurement and insurance.\n- **HR Department**: Maintain medical details and a register of authorised drivers.','EHS-013 Use of Company Vehicles.pdf',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:01:48',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'To establish procedures for the safe use of Amneal Ireland\'s owned or leased vehicles, ensuring compliance with local regulations and safe driving practices.','Applies to the operation of Amneal Ireland owned or leased vehicles on public roadways, private property, and Amneal property. Excludes specialized off-road equipment like forklifts.','- Establishes procedures for the use of Amneal Ireland\'s owned or leased vehicles.\n- Ensures safe operation on public roadways, private property, and Amneal property.\n- Requires drivers to maintain valid licenses and report incidents promptly.','- **Amneal Ireland**: Amneal Ireland Limited, Cahir Road, Cashel, Co. Tipperary, Ireland.\n- **EHS**: Environmental, Health, and Safety.\n- **HR**: Human Resources.\n- **Authorised Persons**: Personnel authorised to operate Amneal Ireland owned or leased vehicles.','- **Authorised Drivers**: Maintain valid licenses, report incidents, and comply with local regulations.\n- **Department Management**: Qualify and authorise employees for vehicle operation.\n- **EHS Department**: Establish safe operation procedures and investigate incidents.\n- **Maintenance Department**: Ensure vehicles are roadworthy.\n- **Finance Department**: Manage vehicle procurement and insurance.\n- **HR Department**: Maintain medical details and a register of authorised drivers.','- **EHS-013**: First Issued.','N/A','- EHS-013.F01-00: Use of Amneal Ireland Company Vehicles Authorisation Form.\n- EHS-013.F01-02: Use of Amneal Ireland Company Vehicles Authorised Users Log.\n- EHS-013.F01-03: Use of Amneal Ireland Company Vehicles Log.\n- ES-008: Reporting and Investigation of Accident, Incident, Near Miss, and Dangerous Occurrence.'),(46,'EHS-014','Movement of Hazardous Liquid Waste to External Site Storage','To establish procedures for the safe movement of hazardous liquid waste from the QC/ARD Laboratory, Production, and Maintenance Departments to external storage areas at Amneal Ireland.\n---\nApplies to the movement of hazardous liquid waste within Amneal Ireland, including proper handling, labeling, and transport to external storage.\n---\n- Describes procedures for moving hazardous liquid waste to external storage.\n- Ensures safe handling and transport of hazardous liquids.\n- Requires proper labeling, PPE, and secondary containment.\n---\n- **EHS-014**: First Issued.\n---\n- **Departmental Personnel**: Follow the procedures outlined in the SOP.\n- **QC/ARD and Warehouse Teams**: Log the movement of liquid waste and maintain records.\n- **EHS Specialist**: Ensure compliance with safety standards.','EHS-014 Movement of Hazardous Liquid to External Site Storage.pdf',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:01:48',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'To establish procedures for the safe movement of hazardous liquid waste from the QC/ARD Laboratory, Production, and Maintenance Departments to external storage areas at Amneal Ireland.','Applies to the movement of hazardous liquid waste within Amneal Ireland, including proper handling, labeling, and transport to external storage.','- Describes procedures for moving hazardous liquid waste to external storage.\n- Ensures safe handling and transport of hazardous liquids.\n- Requires proper labeling, PPE, and secondary containment.','- **SOP**: Standard Operating Procedure.\n- **QC/ARD**: Quality Control/Analytical Research and Development.\n- **PPE**: Personal Protective Equipment.\n- **IPA**: Isopropanol.\n- **API**: Active Pharmaceutical Ingredient.\n- **EHS**: Environment, Health, and Safety.\n- **EHS Specialist**: A trained person knowledgeable about chemical properties and health effects.\n- **Site Leader**: Person responsible for EHS on site.','- **Departmental Personnel**: Follow the procedures outlined in the SOP.\n- **QC/ARD and Warehouse Teams**: Log the movement of liquid waste and maintain records.\n- **EHS Specialist**: Ensure compliance with safety standards.','- **EHS-014**: First Issued.','N/A',NULL),(47,'EHS-017A','Energy Objectives and Targets','To specify the method for setting Energy Objectives and Targets and to monitor their effectiveness, ensuring continual improvement of the Energy Management System (EnMS).\n---\nApplies to Amneal Ireland personnel involved in setting, reviewing, and achieving Energy Objectives and Targets in line with ISO 50001:2018 requirements.\n---\n- Establishes methods for setting and monitoring Energy Objectives and Targets.\n- Ensures continual improvement of the Energy Management System (EnMS).\n- Aligns with ISO 50001:2018 requirements.\n---\n- **EHS-017**: First Issued.\n- **EHS-017A**: SOP and forms transferred to a new template.\n---\n- **Facilities Department**: Develops and assesses Energy Objectives and Targets in conjunction with Site Management and the Energy Management Team.\n- **Site Management**: Works with the Facilities Engineer to develop Energy Objectives and Targets.','EHS-017A Energy Objectives and Targets.pdf',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:01:48',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'To specify the method for setting Energy Objectives and Targets and to monitor their effectiveness, ensuring continual improvement of the Energy Management System (EnMS).','Applies to Amneal Ireland personnel involved in setting, reviewing, and achieving Energy Objectives and Targets in line with ISO 50001:2018 requirements.','- Establishes methods for setting and monitoring Energy Objectives and Targets.\n- Ensures continual improvement of the Energy Management System (EnMS).\n- Aligns with ISO 50001:2018 requirements.','- **Amneal Ireland**: Amneal Ireland Limited, Cahir Road, Cashel, Co. Tipperary, Ireland.\n- **Energy Objective or Target**: A goal set by the company consistent with the Energy Policy and EnMS.\n- **EnMS**: Energy Management System.\n- **SEUs**: Significant Energy Users.\n- **Energy Audits**: Scheduled audits of the Energy Management System.','- **Facilities Department**: Develops and assesses Energy Objectives and Targets in conjunction with Site Management and the Energy Management Team.\n- **Site Management**: Works with the Facilities Engineer to develop Energy Objectives and Targets.','- **EHS-017**: First Issued.\n- **EHS-017A**: SOP and forms transferred to a new template.','EHS-017','- Energy Manual.\n- Energy Policy.'),(48,'EHS-018A','Energy Record Control Policy','To describe the approach for controlling and retaining Energy-related documented information at the Amneal Ireland Cashel facility, ensuring compliance with ISO 50001:2018.\n---\nApplies to the storage and retention of records and documented information related to the ISO 50001:2018 Management Systems at Amneal Ireland.\n---\n- Describes the approach for controlling and retaining Energy-related documented information.\n- Ensures compliance with ISO 50001:2018 requirements.\n- Energy records must be retained for the lifetime of the site.\n---\n- **EHS-018**: First Issued.\n- **EHS-018A**: SOP and forms transferred to a new template.\n---\n- **Facilities Department**: Implements and maintains the procedure, controls equipment maintenance, calibration, and safety assessments.\n- **EHS Department**: Assists the Facilities Department in controlling records and documented information.','EHS-018A Energy Record Control Policy.pdf',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:01:48',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'To describe the approach for controlling and retaining Energy-related documented information at the Amneal Ireland Cashel facility, ensuring compliance with ISO 50001:2018.','Applies to the storage and retention of records and documented information related to the ISO 50001:2018 Management Systems at Amneal Ireland.','- Describes the approach for controlling and retaining Energy-related documented information.\n- Ensures compliance with ISO 50001:2018 requirements.\n- Energy records must be retained for the lifetime of the site.','- **Amneal Ireland**: Amneal Ireland Limited, Cahir Road, Cashel, Co. Tipperary, Ireland.\n- **EHS**: Environmental, Health, and Safety.\n- **EnMS**: Energy Management System.\n- **Energy Records**: Documents or data (manual or electronic) that provide evidence of energy activities and compliance with regulations.\n- **Documented Information**: Information required to be controlled and retained, including processes, operational documentation, and records.','- **Facilities Department**: Implements and maintains the procedure, controls equipment maintenance, calibration, and safety assessments.\n- **EHS Department**: Assists the Facilities Department in controlling records and documented information.','- **EHS-018**: First Issued.\n- **EHS-018A**: SOP and forms transferred to a new template.','EHS-018','- ISO 50001:2018.\n- QM-009: Document Storage and Retention.\n- QM-013: Change Control System.'),(49,'EHS-019B','Identification & Review of Energy Legislative and Other Requirements','To ensure Amneal Ireland is fully familiar with its Energy legislative and other requirements by maintaining, updating, and reviewing the Energy Legal Register.\n---\nApplies to all legislative, regulatory, and other policy requirements related to Energy aspects at Amneal Ireland Cashel.\n---\n- Specifies the method for maintaining, updating, and reviewing the Energy Legal Register.\n- Ensures compliance with Energy legislative and other requirements.\n- Uses Red-on-line for legal register updates.\n---\n- **EHS-019**: First Issued.\n- **EHS-019A**: SOP and forms transferred to a new template.\n- **EHS-019B**: Updated references to Red-on-line and removed references to Pegasus.\n---\n- **EHS Department**: Communicates codes of practice and monitors compliance with Energy legislative obligations.\n- **Facilities Department**: Ensures awareness of current legislation and addresses actions arising from the legal register.','EHS-019B Identification and Review of Energy Legislative and Other Requirements.pdf',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:01:48',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'To ensure Amneal Ireland is fully familiar with its Energy legislative and other requirements by maintaining, updating, and reviewing the Energy Legal Register.','Applies to all legislative, regulatory, and other policy requirements related to Energy aspects at Amneal Ireland Cashel.','- Specifies the method for maintaining, updating, and reviewing the Energy Legal Register.\n- Ensures compliance with Energy legislative and other requirements.\n- Uses Red-on-line for legal register updates.','- **Amneal Ireland**: Amneal Ireland Limited, Cahir Road, Cashel, Co. Tipperary, Ireland.\n- **Antaris**: The licensee provider of the Red-on-line Legal Register.','- **EHS Department**: Communicates codes of practice and monitors compliance with Energy legislative obligations.\n- **Facilities Department**: Ensures awareness of current legislation and addresses actions arising from the legal register.','- **EHS-019**: First Issued.\n- **EHS-019A**: SOP and forms transferred to a new template.\n- **EHS-019B**: Updated references to Red-on-line and removed references to Pegasus.','EHS-019A','- Red-on-line Legal Register (Red-on-line | EHS Solutions (hse-compliance.net)).'),(50,'EHS-020B','Energy Efficient Procurement','To outline the procedure for the energy-efficient procurement of both energy and SEU equipment, ensuring alignment with energy efficiency goals and regulatory requirements.\n---\nApplies to the procurement of Significant Energy Users (e.g., boilers, chillers, compressors, HVAC units) and energy at Amneal Ireland Limited.\n---\n- Outlines the procedure for energy-efficient procurement of energy and SEU equipment.\n- Ensures procurement aligns with energy efficiency goals and regulatory requirements.\n- Considers whole-life costs and environmental impacts of SEUs.\n---\n- **EHS-020**: First Issued.\n- **EHS-020A**: Updated to remove reference to EHS-015 and include reference to PROC-001.\n- **EHS-020B**: SOP and forms transferred to a new template.\n---\n- **Employees**: Investigate energy-efficient options for SEUs.\n- **Facilities Department**: Handle energy procurement, maintain contact with energy efficiency agencies, and ensure SOP compliance.\n- **EHS Department**: Advise on SEU purchases and consider environmental impacts.\n- **Finance Department**: Assist in the SEU procurement process.','EHS-020B Energy Efficient Procurement.pdf',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:01:48',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'To outline the procedure for the energy-efficient procurement of both energy and SEU equipment, ensuring alignment with energy efficiency goals and regulatory requirements.','Applies to the procurement of Significant Energy Users (e.g., boilers, chillers, compressors, HVAC units) and energy at Amneal Ireland Limited.','- Outlines the procedure for energy-efficient procurement of energy and SEU equipment.\n- Ensures procurement aligns with energy efficiency goals and regulatory requirements.\n- Considers whole-life costs and environmental impacts of SEUs.','- **Amneal Ireland**: Amneal Ireland Limited, Cahir Road, Cashel, Co. Tipperary, Ireland.\n- **EHS**: Environmental, Health, and Safety.\n- **Energy Procurement**: Procurement of electricity and gas.\n- **EnMS**: Energy Management System.\n- **EMS**: Energy Monitoring System.\n- **SOP**: Standard Operating Procedure.\n- **HVAC**: Heating, Ventilation, Air Conditioning.\n- **SEU**: Significant Energy User.','- **Employees**: Investigate energy-efficient options for SEUs.\n- **Facilities Department**: Handle energy procurement, maintain contact with energy efficiency agencies, and ensure SOP compliance.\n- **EHS Department**: Advise on SEU purchases and consider environmental impacts.\n- **Finance Department**: Assist in the SEU procurement process.','- **EHS-020**: First Issued.\n- **EHS-020A**: Updated to remove reference to EHS-015 and include reference to PROC-001.\n- **EHS-020B**: SOP and forms transferred to a new template.','EHS-020A','- PROC-001: Procurement to Payment Procedure.'),(51,'EHS-021A','Operation of the Energy Monitoring System (EMS)','The purpose of this SOP is to describe the guidelines for the operation of the Energy Monitoring System (EMS).\n---\nThis SOP will be used by all personnel who are involved in the operation of the EMS system.\n---\nThe procedure describes the steps required to operate the EMS system, including user access levels, baselines, alarms, and preventative maintenance.\n---\nEHS-021: First Issued; SOP and Forms transferred to new Management Software; Removed reference to Action.\n---\nFacilities Department: Responsible for the operation and maintenance of the EMS, performing ongoing checks, and ensuring maintenance is completed. EHS Department: Advise on out-of-specification occurrences and assist in considering environmental effects. IT Department: Complete necessary maintenance through the BMS server maintenance plan.','EHS-021 Operation of the Energy Monitoring System (EMS).pdf',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:01:48',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'The purpose of this SOP is to describe the guidelines for the operation of the Energy Monitoring System (EMS).','This SOP will be used by all personnel who are involved in the operation of the EMS system.','The procedure describes the steps required to operate the EMS system, including user access levels, baselines, alarms, and preventative maintenance.','Amneal Ireland: Amneal Ireland Limited, Cahir Road, Cashel, Co. Tipperary, Ireland; EHS: Environmental, Health and Safety; BMS: Building Management System; EnMS: Energy Management System; EMS: Energy Monitoring System; SOP: Standard Operating Procedure; HVAC: Heating, Ventilation, Air Conditioning; SEU: Significant Energy User; Maximo: On-site Computer Maintenance Management System','Facilities Department: Responsible for the operation and maintenance of the EMS, performing ongoing checks, and ensuring maintenance is completed. EHS Department: Advise on out-of-specification occurrences and assist in considering environmental effects. IT Department: Complete necessary maintenance through the BMS server maintenance plan.','EHS-021: First Issued; SOP and Forms transferred to new Management Software; Removed reference to Action.','EHS-021','N/A'),(52,'EHS-003A','Environmental Aspects and Impacts','The purpose of this procedure is to provide a system to identify environmental aspects of the Amneal Ireland Cashel facility\'s activities, products, and services and their impact on the environment, to enable the site to consider actions to mitigate these impacts and comply with ISO 14001:2015.\n---\nThis SOP applies to all current and past activities, products, and services or new developments, or new or modified activities, to identify those which have a significant impact on the environment.\n---\nThe procedure provides a system to identify environmental aspects and their impacts, assess their significance, and prioritize actions to mitigate impacts.\n---\nEHS-003: First Issued; EHS-003A: Editorial changes to include ISO 14001:2015 requirements, clarified frequency of occurrence score, removed activity and score from summary list, removed lead from potential negative impacts, clarified which management of change documents are reviewed, added risks and opportunities section.\n---\nEHS Manager: Ensures the Aspects/Impacts register is reviewed and updated, and significant environmental aspects are prioritized in the annual objectives discussion during management review.','EHS-003 Environmental Aspects and Impacts.pdf',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:01:48',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'The purpose of this procedure is to provide a system to identify environmental aspects of the Amneal Ireland Cashel facility\'s activities, products, and services and their impact on the environment, to enable the site to consider actions to mitigate these impacts and comply with ISO 14001:2015.','This SOP applies to all current and past activities, products, and services or new developments, or new or modified activities, to identify those which have a significant impact on the environment.','The procedure provides a system to identify environmental aspects and their impacts, assess their significance, and prioritize actions to mitigate impacts.','Amneal Ireland: Amneal Ireland Limited, Cahir Road, Cashel, Co. Tipperary, Ireland; Change Control: A documented account of a change to be made to equipment or process; Environmental Aspect: An element of the Site activities, products, or services that can interact with the environment; Environmental Impact: Any changes to the environment, whether adverse or beneficial, wholly or partially resulting from the Site\'s activities, products, or services; Aspects/Impacts Register: Register which rates the impacts of each aspect on the environment; EHS: Environmental, Health and Safety.','EHS Manager: Ensures the Aspects/Impacts register is reviewed and updated, and significant environmental aspects are prioritized in the annual objectives discussion during management review.','EHS-003: First Issued; EHS-003A: Editorial changes to include ISO 14001:2015 requirements, clarified frequency of occurrence score, removed activity and score from summary list, removed lead from potential negative impacts, clarified which management of change documents are reviewed, added risks and opportunities section.','EHS-003','ISO 14001:2015; QM-013 Change Control System'),(53,'EHS-005','CHEMICAL SUBSTANCE MANAGEMENT','To manage chemical substances safely and ensure compliance with regulations.\n---\nApplies to all chemical substances used or stored on site.\n---\nChemical Inventory Database, Safety Data Sheets (SDS), Labelling, Purchase of Chemicals, Chemical Compatibility, Handling and Storage, Contractors\n---\n• Removed tables containing internal and external issues and included as Appendices • Removed tables containing interested parties and included as Appendices • Updated Appendices numbers • Added reference to ISO standard clauses to Chapter titles • Updated Reviewers\n---\nEHS, PO requestors, Vendors, Contractors, Project Managers','EHS-005 Chemical Substance Management.pdf',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:01:48',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'To manage chemical substances safely and ensure compliance with regulations.','Applies to all chemical substances used or stored on site.','Chemical Inventory Database, Safety Data Sheets (SDS), Labelling, Purchase of Chemicals, Chemical Compatibility, Handling and Storage, Contractors',NULL,'EHS, PO requestors, Vendors, Contractors, Project Managers','• Removed tables containing internal and external issues and included as Appendices • Removed tables containing interested parties and included as Appendices • Updated Appendices numbers • Added reference to ISO standard clauses to Chapter titles • Updated Reviewers',NULL,'ES-006 Spill Response Procedure, Chemical Risk Assessment form'),(54,'EHS-006B','ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH & SAFETY OBJECTIVES','To specify the method by which Environment Health and Safety objectives are set and how their effectiveness is monitored to ensure continual improvement in the EHS management system.\n---\nApplies to Amneal Ireland personnel involved in setting, specifying, reviewing, and achieving EHS objectives in line with legislative and significant aspects and the requirements of ISO14001:2015 and ISO45001:2018.\n---\nObjectives and Targets shall be established considering operational and business requirements, EHS Policy, compliance obligations, significant environmental aspects, environmental risks and opportunities, Safety Statement, and risk assessments. Each objective shall have an owner, required resources, and effective date. Objectives are reviewed and updated as needed.\n---\nEHS-006 - First Issued. EHS-006A (09-Mar-2018) - Editorial changes to include ISO14001:2015 requirements, EHS Specialist replaced by EHS Manager, Targets removed, definition of EHS objective modified, environmental risks and opportunities added, required resources included. EHS-006B (17-Apr-19) - OHSAS18001:2007 changed to ISO45001:2018.\n---\nEHS Manager - Develop site EHS Objectives with the Site Director and ensure regular assessment. Site Director - Develop EHS Objectives with the EHS Manager.','EHS-006B Environmental Health and Safety Objectives and Targets.pdf',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:01:48',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'To specify the method by which Environment Health and Safety objectives are set and how their effectiveness is monitored to ensure continual improvement in the EHS management system.','Applies to Amneal Ireland personnel involved in setting, specifying, reviewing, and achieving EHS objectives in line with legislative and significant aspects and the requirements of ISO14001:2015 and ISO45001:2018.','Objectives and Targets shall be established considering operational and business requirements, EHS Policy, compliance obligations, significant environmental aspects, environmental risks and opportunities, Safety Statement, and risk assessments. Each objective shall have an owner, required resources, and effective date. Objectives are reviewed and updated as needed.','Amneal Ireland - Amneal Ireland Limited Cahir Road, Cashel, Co. Tipperary, Ireland. EHS Objective - a goal consistent with the site EHS policy and arising from the site environmental review or Occupational Health and Safety performance.','EHS Manager - Develop site EHS Objectives with the Site Director and ensure regular assessment. Site Director - Develop EHS Objectives with the EHS Manager.','EHS-006 - First Issued. EHS-006A (09-Mar-2018) - Editorial changes to include ISO14001:2015 requirements, EHS Specialist replaced by EHS Manager, Targets removed, definition of EHS objective modified, environmental risks and opportunities added, required resources included. EHS-006B (17-Apr-19) - OHSAS18001:2007 changed to ISO45001:2018.','EHS-006A','Aspects and Impacts Register, EHS Policy, Amneal Risk assessment folder'),(55,'EHS-007A','ENVIRONMENT, HEALTH & SAFETY COMMUNICATION AND COMPLAINT PROCEDURE','To describe the procedure for handling EHS-related communications and external complaints.\n---\nApplies to all EHS communications and external complaints received at the Amneal Ireland facility.\n---\nInternal communication encourages employee participation in EHS practices, risk assessments, and incident investigations. External complaints are handled through a formal procedure, with forms retained for three years. EHS information is communicated via intranet, noticeboards, and monthly meetings.\n---\nEHS-007 - First Issued. EHS-007A (09-Mar-2018) - Editorial changes to include ISO14001:2015 requirements, noted use of intranet for internal EHS communication, and retention of complaint forms for 3 years.\n---\nEHS Department - Maintain the procedure and handle external complaints. Employees and Security - Direct external complaints to the Site Director via EHS. Site Director - Approve responses to external complaints.','EHS-007A Environmental Health & Safety Communication & Compliant Procedure.pdf',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:01:48',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'To describe the procedure for handling EHS-related communications and external complaints.','Applies to all EHS communications and external complaints received at the Amneal Ireland facility.','Internal communication encourages employee participation in EHS practices, risk assessments, and incident investigations. External complaints are handled through a formal procedure, with forms retained for three years. EHS information is communicated via intranet, noticeboards, and monthly meetings.','Amneal Ireland - Amneal Ireland Limited Cahir Road, Cashel, Co. Tipperary, Ireland. EHS - Environmental, Health and Safety.','EHS Department - Maintain the procedure and handle external complaints. Employees and Security - Direct external complaints to the Site Director via EHS. Site Director - Approve responses to external complaints.','EHS-007 - First Issued. EHS-007A (09-Mar-2018) - Editorial changes to include ISO14001:2015 requirements, noted use of intranet for internal EHS communication, and retention of complaint forms for 3 years.','EHS-007','FM-EHS-009-00 External Communication and Complaint form, Emergency Response Plan'),(56,'EHS-008C','ENVIRONMENT, HEALTH & SAFETY & ENERGY MANAGEMENT REVIEW','To describe the procedure for the Environment, Health and Safety, and Energy Management Review program at the Amneal Ireland Cashel facility.\n---\nApplies to all EHS and Energy Management Review meetings conducted at the Amneal Ireland Cashel facility.\n---\nEHS and Energy Management Review meetings are held annually to assess the suitability, adequacy, and effectiveness of the site EHS and Energy program. The review considers action items, compliance obligations, significant environmental aspects, risks, opportunities, and energy performance. Minutes are retained for 3 years.\n---\nEHS-008 - First Issued. EHS-008A (08-Mar-2018) - Editorial changes to include ISO14001:2015 requirements, replaced Specialist with Manager, and added discussion items. EHS-008B (18-Apr-2019) - Added Energy to EHS references, included Facilities Engineer, and added energy-related discussion items. EHS-008C - SOP and forms transferred to a new template, titles reworded.\n---\nEHS and Facilities - Ensure annual review meetings, provide necessary documentation, and retain meeting minutes for 3 years. Senior Leadership Team - Attend meetings, participate in discussions, and follow up on action items.','EHS-008C EHS Management Review.pdf',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:02:54',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'To describe the procedure for the Environment, Health and Safety, and Energy Management Review program at the Amneal Ireland Cashel facility.','Applies to all EHS and Energy Management Review meetings conducted at the Amneal Ireland Cashel facility.','EHS and Energy Management Review meetings are held annually to assess the suitability, adequacy, and effectiveness of the site EHS and Energy program. The review considers action items, compliance obligations, significant environmental aspects, risks, opportunities, and energy performance. Minutes are retained for 3 years.','Amneal Ireland - Amneal Ireland Limited Cahir Road, Cashel, Co. Tipperary, Ireland. EHS - Environmental, Health and Safety. Management Review - A forum for discussion and improvement of EHS and Energy performance. EMS - Environmental Management System.','EHS and Facilities - Ensure annual review meetings, provide necessary documentation, and retain meeting minutes for 3 years. Senior Leadership Team - Attend meetings, participate in discussions, and follow up on action items.','EHS-008 - First Issued. EHS-008A (08-Mar-2018) - Editorial changes to include ISO14001:2015 requirements, replaced Specialist with Manager, and added discussion items. EHS-008B (18-Apr-2019) - Added Energy to EHS references, included Facilities Engineer, and added energy-related discussion items. EHS-008C - SOP and forms transferred to a new template, titles reworded.','EHS-008B','EHS Policy, Aspects Impacts Register'),(57,'EHS-009B','PREPARATION AND CONTROL OF ENVIRONMENT, HEALTH & SAFETY STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURES','To outline the procedure for preparing and controlling Environment, Health, and Safety Standard Operating Procedures.\n---\nApplies to the development, implementation, and maintenance of EHS documents in compliance with ISO standards.\n---\nEHS documents are developed, implemented, and maintained in compliance with ISO 45001:2018 and ISO 14001:2015. Only soft copies are retained, with master documents stored in the \'EHS Integrated procedures\' folder. Obsolete documents are retained by EHS.\n---\nEHS-009 - First Issued. EHS-009A (09-Mar-2018) - Editorial changes to include ISO14001:2015 requirements, added definition of SOP, and replaced Engineering Manager with Engineering Director or designee. EHS-009B (17-Apr-19) - Changed OHSAS18001:2007 to ISO45001:2018.\n---\nEHS function - Develop, implement, and maintain documents. Engineering Director or designee - Approve new and revised documents.','EHS-009B Preperation and Control of EHS SOP\'s.pdf',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:02:54',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'To outline the procedure for preparing and controlling Environment, Health, and Safety Standard Operating Procedures.','Applies to the development, implementation, and maintenance of EHS documents in compliance with ISO standards.','EHS documents are developed, implemented, and maintained in compliance with ISO 45001:2018 and ISO 14001:2015. Only soft copies are retained, with master documents stored in the \'EHS Integrated procedures\' folder. Obsolete documents are retained by EHS.',NULL,'EHS function - Develop, implement, and maintain documents. Engineering Director or designee - Approve new and revised documents.','EHS-009 - First Issued. EHS-009A (09-Mar-2018) - Editorial changes to include ISO14001:2015 requirements, added definition of SOP, and replaced Engineering Manager with Engineering Director or designee. EHS-009B (17-Apr-19) - Changed OHSAS18001:2007 to ISO45001:2018.',NULL,'QM-001 Preparation and Control of Standard Operating Procedures'),(58,'EHS-010B','ENVIRONMENT, HEALTH, SAFETY & ENERGY RECORD CONTROL POLICY','The purpose of this document is to describe the approach for controlling and retaining Environmental, Health, Safety & Energy documented information at the Amneal Ireland Cashel facility.\n---\nAmneal Ireland have established this policy to control on-site storage and retention of records and documented information that relates to the ISO45001:2018, ISO14001:2015 and ISO50001:2018 Management Systems and the requirements therein.\n---\nDocuments required by the company and by ISO45001:2018, ISO14001:2015, and ISO50001:2018 Management Standards shall be stored and retained in the EHS Department and Document Control Centre for the retention period defined in Table 1.\n---\nEHS-010 - First Issued\nEHS-010A - 08-Mar-2018 - Editorial change to include the standard requirements identified in ISO14001:2015\nEHS-010B - 17-Apr-19 - Updated to include ISO50001:2018 throughout. OHSAS18001:2007 replaced with ISO45001:2018.\n---\nThe EHS Department is responsible for the implementation and maintenance of this procedure and control of certain records and documented information.\nThe Engineering Department is responsible for the control of equipment maintenance, calibration and safety assessments in conjunction with relevant departments and control of certain records and documented information.\nThe Human Resources(HR) Department is responsible for the control of all employee Medical and Occupational Health records. Information on competence and job specific training is shared between the HR department and the EHS team.','EHS-010B EHS Record Retention Policy.pdf',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:02:54',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'The purpose of this document is to describe the approach for controlling and retaining Environmental, Health, Safety & Energy documented information at the Amneal Ireland Cashel facility.','Amneal Ireland have established this policy to control on-site storage and retention of records and documented information that relates to the ISO45001:2018, ISO14001:2015 and ISO50001:2018 Management Systems and the requirements therein.','Documents required by the company and by ISO45001:2018, ISO14001:2015, and ISO50001:2018 Management Standards shall be stored and retained in the EHS Department and Document Control Centre for the retention period defined in Table 1.','Amneal Ireland: Amneal Ireland Limited Cahir Road, Cashel, Co. Tipperary, Ireland.\nEHS-Environmental, Health and Safety\nErgo-ergonomic\nHealth and safety Records - Any document in which data is held or stored manually or electronically.\nDocumented information – The Environmental Information required to be controlled and retained by Amneal including processes related to the Environmental Management System, operational documentation (including procedures) and records stating results and providing evidence of activities performed.','The EHS Department is responsible for the implementation and maintenance of this procedure and control of certain records and documented information.\nThe Engineering Department is responsible for the control of equipment maintenance, calibration and safety assessments in conjunction with relevant departments and control of certain records and documented information.\nThe Human Resources(HR) Department is responsible for the control of all employee Medical and Occupational Health records. Information on competence and job specific training is shared between the HR department and the EHS team.','EHS-010 - First Issued\nEHS-010A - 08-Mar-2018 - Editorial change to include the standard requirements identified in ISO14001:2015\nEHS-010B - 17-Apr-19 - Updated to include ISO50001:2018 throughout. OHSAS18001:2007 replaced with ISO45001:2018.','EHS-010A','International Standard ISO45001:2018\nInternational Standard ISO14001:2015\nInternational Standard ISO50001:2018\nQM-009 Document Storage and Retention'),(59,'ES-001J','MATERIAL DESTRUCTION AND WASTE MANAGEMENT PROCEDURE','To describe the procedure for the effective management and disposal of all hazardous, non-hazardous, biological, and contaminated waste and waste packing materials generated by the Amneal Ireland facility in accordance with local regulations and corporate requirements.\n---\nThis Procedure applies to the management of waste generated at the Amneal Ireland facility.\n---\nThe procedure outlines the management and disposal of hazardous, non-hazardous, biological, and contaminated waste, including material destruction. It includes steps for waste segregation, labeling, and disposal, as well as responsibilities for different departments.\n---\nES-001: 26-Apr-2016 - First Issued, ES-001A: 17-Feb-2017 - Updated text, replaced C1 form with WTF, removed DGSA reference, added new points, updated Table 1, ES-001B: 07-Apr-2017 - Added driver\'s name, updated Table 1, ES-001C: 02-Feb-2018 - Added instructions for labeling and waste log, updated Table 1, ES-001D: 29-Mar-2018 - Updated waste transfer form retention, added torque instruction, updated Table 1, ES-001E: 30-Oct-2018 - Added Microbiology Laboratory responsibilities, updated Table 1, ES-001F: 29-Mar-2019 - Updated template, definitions, and responsibilities, updated Table 1, ES-001G: 15-Mar-2022 - Updated logo and template, ES-001H: 22-Jun-2022 - Added PD Lab, updated Table 1, ES-001I: 05-Oct-2023 - Updated decanting instructions, reviewed Table 1, ES-001J: 31-Jul-24 - Updated FM-ES-006.\n---\nEach employee is responsible for the correct segregation and in-house disposal of non-hazardous waste streams. Project Managers ensure contractor compliance. Departments manage waste labeling, segregation, and packaging. Manufacturing transfers waste to the airlock. Contract cleaners handle waste movement and decanting. Warehouse personnel collect and store waste. QC/ARD/PD and Microbiology Laboratory personnel manage specific waste types. EHS oversees overall waste management, appoints licensed contractors, and maintains documentation.','ES-001J IMaterial Destruction & Waste Management Procedure.pdf',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:02:54',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'To describe the procedure for the effective management and disposal of all hazardous, non-hazardous, biological, and contaminated waste and waste packing materials generated by the Amneal Ireland facility in accordance with local regulations and corporate requirements.','This Procedure applies to the management of waste generated at the Amneal Ireland facility.','The procedure outlines the management and disposal of hazardous, non-hazardous, biological, and contaminated waste, including material destruction. It includes steps for waste segregation, labeling, and disposal, as well as responsibilities for different departments.','API: Active Pharmaceutical Ingredient, DGSA: Dangerous Goods Safety Advisor, EWC: European Waste Catalogue, IPA: Isopropyl Alcohol, PPE: Personal Protective Equipment, IBC: Intermediate Bulk Containers, SOP: Standard Operating Procedure, WTF: Waste Transfer Form, TSDF: Treatment, Storage & Disposal Facility, Waste: A material, substance or by-product eliminated or discarded as no longer useful, Contaminated Waste: Impure waste by exposure to or addition of a harmful, poisonous or polluting substance, Hazardous Waste: Any waste which by reason of any of its physical, chemical, reactive, toxic, flammable, explosive or corrosive characteristics causes danger or is likely to cause danger to health or environment, Biological Waste: Any material that contains or has been contaminated by a biohazardous agent, Bio Medical Waste: Discarded medicines including damaged or rejected filled containers, PM: Preventative maintenance, EHS: Environmental, Health and Safety, QC/ARD: Quality Control/Analytical Research and Development, Halogenated Waste: Organic solvent waste containing halogenic atoms, Non-Halogenated Waste: All other solvents not mentioned in section 4.18, Amneal Ireland: Amneal Ireland Limited Cahir Road, Cashel, Co. Tipperary, Ireland, PD Lab: Product Development Laboratory, Ullage: Loss of liquid, by evaporation or leakage.','Each employee is responsible for the correct segregation and in-house disposal of non-hazardous waste streams. Project Managers ensure contractor compliance. Departments manage waste labeling, segregation, and packaging. Manufacturing transfers waste to the airlock. Contract cleaners handle waste movement and decanting. Warehouse personnel collect and store waste. QC/ARD/PD and Microbiology Laboratory personnel manage specific waste types. EHS oversees overall waste management, appoints licensed contractors, and maintains documentation.','ES-001: 26-Apr-2016 - First Issued, ES-001A: 17-Feb-2017 - Updated text, replaced C1 form with WTF, removed DGSA reference, added new points, updated Table 1, ES-001B: 07-Apr-2017 - Added driver\'s name, updated Table 1, ES-001C: 02-Feb-2018 - Added instructions for labeling and waste log, updated Table 1, ES-001D: 29-Mar-2018 - Updated waste transfer form retention, added torque instruction, updated Table 1, ES-001E: 30-Oct-2018 - Added Microbiology Laboratory responsibilities, updated Table 1, ES-001F: 29-Mar-2019 - Updated template, definitions, and responsibilities, updated Table 1, ES-001G: 15-Mar-2022 - Updated logo and template, ES-001H: 22-Jun-2022 - Added PD Lab, updated Table 1, ES-001I: 05-Oct-2023 - Updated decanting instructions, reviewed Table 1, ES-001J: 31-Jul-24 - Updated FM-ES-006.','ES-001I','FM-ES-006: Hazardous waste consignment check list, FM-ES-001: Internal Waste Log, FM-ES-002: Waste Identification label'),(60,'ES-002C','OPERATION, CLEANING AND STORAGE OF POWERED AIR PURIFYING RESPIRATORS','To establish a procedure for the operation, cleaning, and storage of Powered Air Purifying Respirators (PAPRs) and personal hoods to fulfil the requirements of the Safety Health and Welfare at Work (General Applications) Regulations 2007-2020, Part 2, Chapter 3: Use of Personal Protective Equipment at Work.\n---\nThis SOP applies to all personnel and areas where Powered Air Purifying Respirators are required. The requirements of this SOP are in conjunction with ES-005 Usage of Personal Protection Equipment.\n---\nThe procedure outlines the operation, cleaning, and storage of Powered Air Purifying Respirators (PAPRs) and personal hoods. It includes hazard identification, risk assessment, selection, and proper use of PAPRs, as well as cleaning and storage protocols.\n---\nES-002: 10-Nov-2017 - First Issued, ES-002A: 23-Nov-2018 - Updated wording and added new sub-sections, ES-002B: 24-Jan-2020 - Updated to new Amneal Logo, ES-002C: 22-Jan-2020 - Updated Safety Health and Welfare at Work Regulations, added OJT reference, updated calibration instructions, and removed Scott PAPR references.\n---\nEHS Department: Develop and maintain a PPE matrix, assist in hazard identification and risk assessment, provide advice on PAPR use, and replace damaged PAPRs. All Employees: Use appropriate PPE, report damage or concerns, and ensure proper operation, calibration, maintenance, cleaning, and storage of PAPRs. Area Managers: Provide resources, ensure training, and ensure proper use and storage of PAPRs.','ES-002C Op, Clean & Storage of Powered Air Purifying Respirators.pdf',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:02:54',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'To establish a procedure for the operation, cleaning, and storage of Powered Air Purifying Respirators (PAPRs) and personal hoods to fulfil the requirements of the Safety Health and Welfare at Work (General Applications) Regulations 2007-2020, Part 2, Chapter 3: Use of Personal Protective Equipment at Work.','This SOP applies to all personnel and areas where Powered Air Purifying Respirators are required. The requirements of this SOP are in conjunction with ES-005 Usage of Personal Protection Equipment.','The procedure outlines the operation, cleaning, and storage of Powered Air Purifying Respirators (PAPRs) and personal hoods. It includes hazard identification, risk assessment, selection, and proper use of PAPRs, as well as cleaning and storage protocols.','Amneal Ireland: Amneal Ireland Limited Cahir Road, Cashel, Co. Tipperary, Ireland, Control or Control measures: A process, policy, device, practice or action designed to eliminate or minimize a risk, PAPR’s: Powered Air Purifying Respirators, EN: EN followed by a series of numbers means relevant European Standard, Elimination: The highest level in the hierarchy of controls which involves the removal of a hazard or exposure, Engineering Control: Methods of eliminating or reducing exposure to chemical, physical, or biological agents by installing or modifying equipment, Harm: Damage to human health or the environment, Hazard Assessment: The process of identifying hazards and prescribing controls to reduce risk, Hierarchy of Control: The practice of selecting and applying controls in the hierarchy of elimination, substitution, engineering, administrative, and PPE, Maintenance: Cleaning, inspection, and repair of PPE to ensure it functions to design specification, OEL: Occupational Exposure Limit – Upper limit on the acceptable concentration of a hazardous substance in workplace air, PPE: Personal Protective Equipment - Items worn to protect an individual from risks, Residual Risk: Risk remaining after implementation of risk control measures, Risk Assessment: The process of hazard identification, risk analysis, and risk control, Risk Control Measure: Workplace EHS safeguards using the hierarchy of control, Substitution: Implementation of a less hazardous operation or material, ES: Environmental Health and Safety, MF: Manufacturing, QA: Quality Assurance, IPA: Isopropyl Alcohol, SOP: Standard Operating Procedure, OJT: On the job training.','EHS Department: Develop and maintain a PPE matrix, assist in hazard identification and risk assessment, provide advice on PAPR use, and replace damaged PAPRs. All Employees: Use appropriate PPE, report damage or concerns, and ensure proper operation, calibration, maintenance, cleaning, and storage of PAPRs. Area Managers: Provide resources, ensure training, and ensure proper use and storage of PAPRs.','ES-002: 10-Nov-2017 - First Issued, ES-002A: 23-Nov-2018 - Updated wording and added new sub-sections, ES-002B: 24-Jan-2020 - Updated to new Amneal Logo, ES-002C: 22-Jan-2020 - Updated Safety Health and Welfare at Work Regulations, added OJT reference, updated calibration instructions, and removed Scott PAPR references.','ES-002B','ES-005: Usage of Personal Protective Equipment, FM-ES-005: PPE Matrix, ES-009: Environmental Health and Safety Risk Assessment Procedure, N/A: Safety Health and Welfare at Work (General Applications) Regulations 2007, Part 2, Chapter 3: Use of Personal Protective Equipment at Work, MF-009: Gowning Procedure for Entering and Exiting the Inhalation Areas.'),(61,'ES-003A','USE OF FACE MASKS/SHIELDS IN THE INHALATION FACILITY, WAREHOUSE, QC CHEMISTRY AND QC MICROBIOLOGY LABORATORIES AT AMNEAL IRELAND','To provide instruction for the proper use and disposal of face masks/shields in the Inhalation Facility, Warehouse, QC Chemistry, and QC Microbiology Laboratories at Amneal Ireland in line with Irish Government and CDC recommendations.\n---\nThe scope of this SOP is the proper use and disposal of face masks/shields in the Inhalation Facility, Warehouse, QC Chemistry, and QC Microbiology Laboratories by Amneal Personnel, Contractors, and Visitors. General office areas and maintenance areas are out of scope.\n---\nThe procedure provides instructions for the proper use and disposal of face masks/shields in the Inhalation Facility, Warehouse, QC Chemistry, and QC Microbiology Laboratories. It includes guidelines for donning and removing masks/shields, sanitization, and disposal in line with Irish Government and CDC recommendations.\n---\nES-003: 19-Aug-2020 - Initial, ES-003A: 2.2~<e~ 2e>2c - Updated to include existing control measures, clarified requirements in CNC office area (XP-15), and realigned numbering.\n---\nAll personnel wearing face masks/shields must be trained and adhere to this procedure. Personnel hosting visitors must ensure visitors follow the procedure. EHS is responsible for maintaining an overall stock of face masks/shields.','ES-003A Use of Face Masks Shields in the Inhalation Facility.pdf',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:02:54',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'To provide instruction for the proper use and disposal of face masks/shields in the Inhalation Facility, Warehouse, QC Chemistry, and QC Microbiology Laboratories at Amneal Ireland in line with Irish Government and CDC recommendations.','The scope of this SOP is the proper use and disposal of face masks/shields in the Inhalation Facility, Warehouse, QC Chemistry, and QC Microbiology Laboratories by Amneal Personnel, Contractors, and Visitors. General office areas and maintenance areas are out of scope.','The procedure provides instructions for the proper use and disposal of face masks/shields in the Inhalation Facility, Warehouse, QC Chemistry, and QC Microbiology Laboratories. It includes guidelines for donning and removing masks/shields, sanitization, and disposal in line with Irish Government and CDC recommendations.','SOP: Standard Operating Procedure, QC/ARD: Quality Control Analytical Research and Development, EHS: Environmental Health and Safety, Face mask (Medical Mask): Device covering the mouth, nose, and chin, compliant with EN 14683:2014, Face mask, Non-Medical Mask: Covering over the mouth, nose, and chin, not permitted in the Inhalation facility, Face shield: Device to protect eyes and face from bodily fluids or infectious materials, CDC: Center for Disease Control, PPE: Personal Protective Equipment, IPA: Isopropyl Alcohol, FDA: Food and Drug Administration, MF: Manufacturing, QA: Quality Assurance.','All personnel wearing face masks/shields must be trained and adhere to this procedure. Personnel hosting visitors must ensure visitors follow the procedure. EHS is responsible for maintaining an overall stock of face masks/shields.','ES-003: 19-Aug-2020 - Initial, ES-003A: 2.2~<e~ 2e>2c - Updated to include existing control measures, clarified requirements in CNC office area (XP-15), and realigned numbering.','ES-003','ES-001: Material Destruction and Waste Management Procedure, MF-009: Gowning Procedure for Entering and Exiting the Inhalation Areas, MM-003: Garbing Procedure for Warehouse Entry, QC-029: Gowning Procedure for QC/ARD Laboratory Entry, QC-073: Gowning Procedure for the Microbiology Laboratory, FDA Good Manufacturing Practice Considerations for Responding to COVID-19 Infection in Employees in Drug and Biological Products Manufacturing (June 2020).'),(62,'ES-005A','USAGE OF PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT (PPE)','To establish a procedure for managing the use of personal protective equipment (PPE) including eye, hand, foot, and body protection, in compliance with the Safety Health and Welfare at Work (General Applications) Regulations 2007.\n---\nThis SOP applies to all PPE selected, used, and maintained on site and to all areas where PPE is required.\n---\nThe procedure outlines the management of personal protective equipment (PPE) including eye, hand, foot, and body protection. It includes hazard identification, risk assessment, selection, use, maintenance, and storage of PPE in compliance with the Safety Health and Welfare at Work (General Applications) Regulations 2007.\n---\nES-005: 22-Dec-2016 - First Issued, ES-005A: C·S-A·U=a·O - SOP and forms transferred to new template.\n---\nEHS Department: Develop and maintain a PPE matrix, provide technical guidance, assist in hazard identification, and support training. All Employees: Understand hazards, use appropriate PPE, and report damage. Area Managers: Provide resources, ensure training, and ensure proper use and storage of PPE.','ES-005A Usage of Personal Protective Equipment (PPE).pdf',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:02:54',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'To establish a procedure for managing the use of personal protective equipment (PPE) including eye, hand, foot, and body protection, in compliance with the Safety Health and Welfare at Work (General Applications) Regulations 2007.','This SOP applies to all PPE selected, used, and maintained on site and to all areas where PPE is required.','The procedure outlines the management of personal protective equipment (PPE) including eye, hand, foot, and body protection. It includes hazard identification, risk assessment, selection, use, maintenance, and storage of PPE in compliance with the Safety Health and Welfare at Work (General Applications) Regulations 2007.','Amneal Ireland: Amneal Ireland Limited Cahir Road, Cashel, Co. Tipperary, Ireland, Control or Control measures: A process, policy, device, practice or action designed to eliminate or minimize a risk, dBA: A-weighted decibels – Expression of the relative loudness of sounds in air, EN: EN followed by a series of numbers means relevant European Standard, Elimination: The highest level in the hierarchy of controls involving the removal of a hazard, Engineering Control: Methods of reducing exposure to hazards by modifying equipment, Harm: Damage to human health or the environment, Hazard Assessment: The process of identifying hazards and prescribing controls, Hierarchy of Control: The practice of selecting controls in the order of elimination, substitution, engineering, administrative, and PPE, Maintenance: Cleaning, inspection, and repair of PPE, OEL: Occupational Exposure Limit – Upper limit on the acceptable concentration of a hazardous substance, PPE: Personal Protective Equipment - Items worn to protect against risks, Residual Risk: Risk remaining after control measures, RPE: Respiratory Protective Equipment, Risk Analysis: Systematic process to understand and reduce risk, Risk Assessment: The process of hazard identification, risk analysis, and control, Risk Control Measure: Safeguards using the hierarchy of control, Substitution: Implementation of a less hazardous operation or material, TWA: Time-Weighted Average - Daily exposure to a hazardous substance averaged to an 8-hour workday.','EHS Department: Develop and maintain a PPE matrix, provide technical guidance, assist in hazard identification, and support training. All Employees: Understand hazards, use appropriate PPE, and report damage. Area Managers: Provide resources, ensure training, and ensure proper use and storage of PPE.','ES-005: 22-Dec-2016 - First Issued, ES-005A: C·S-A·U=a·O - SOP and forms transferred to new template.','ES-005','FM-ES-012: PPE Matrix, ES-009: Environmental Health and Safety Risk Assessment Procedure, N/A: Safety Health and Welfare at Work (General Applications) Regulations 2007, Part 2, Chapter 3: Use of Personal Protective Equipment at Work.'),(63,'ES-006B','SPILL RESPONSE PROCEDURE','To establish a spill response procedure to ensure a coordinated response in the event of a spill, protecting health, safety, and the environment, and ensuring efficient incident reporting and investigation.\n---\nThe scope applies to the prevention of and response to spills by the Emergency Response Team (ERT), employees, and contractors. It includes all minor and major spills on site.\n---\nThe procedure outlines the response to spills, including small and large hazardous liquid and solid spills, propellant HFA spills, biological spills, and spills into surface water drains or soil. It includes steps for containment, cleanup, and reporting, as well as responsibilities for the Emergency Response Team (ERT), employees, and external emergency services.\n---\nES-006: 03-Feb-2017 - First Issued, ES-006A: 23-Jan-2020 - Updated to Amneal new logo, ES-006B: 02-Oct-2023 - Updated ERT responsibilities, added biological spill response, and minor editorial changes.\n---\nEmergency Response Team (ERT): Carry out emergency procedures, respond to major spills, and participate in incident investigations. All Employees: Prevent spills, control and clean small spills, and report large spills. Facilities Team: Shut off valves and assist in spill cleanup. Microbiological Department: Control and clean biological spills. External Emergency Services: Handle major chemical or biological spills.','ES-006B Spill Response Procedure.pdf',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:02:54',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'To establish a spill response procedure to ensure a coordinated response in the event of a spill, protecting health, safety, and the environment, and ensuring efficient incident reporting and investigation.','The scope applies to the prevention of and response to spills by the Emergency Response Team (ERT), employees, and contractors. It includes all minor and major spills on site.','The procedure outlines the response to spills, including small and large hazardous liquid and solid spills, propellant HFA spills, biological spills, and spills into surface water drains or soil. It includes steps for containment, cleanup, and reporting, as well as responsibilities for the Emergency Response Team (ERT), employees, and external emergency services.','Amneal Ireland: Amneal Ireland Limited, Cahir Road, Cashel, Co. Tipperary, Ireland, Emergency Response: Immediate actions taken to mitigate the impact of an emergency, Emergency Response Team (ERT): A site-level team of specialized individuals for emergency response, Environmental Event: Any spill, release, or non-compliance with environmental regulations, HFA: Hydrofluoroalkane, a propellant used for metered-dose inhalers, Release: An environmental event, Rescue: Activities to locate and remove endangered persons from danger, Response: Activities in preparation for an emergency until emergency apparatus arrives, SDS: Safety Data Sheet, a document detailing the properties and hazards of a chemical, Spill: An environmental event categorized into small, large, and biological spills.','Emergency Response Team (ERT): Carry out emergency procedures, respond to major spills, and participate in incident investigations. All Employees: Prevent spills, control and clean small spills, and report large spills. Facilities Team: Shut off valves and assist in spill cleanup. Microbiological Department: Control and clean biological spills. External Emergency Services: Handle major chemical or biological spills.','ES-006: 03-Feb-2017 - First Issued, ES-006A: 23-Jan-2020 - Updated to Amneal new logo, ES-006B: 02-Oct-2023 - Updated ERT responsibilities, added biological spill response, and minor editorial changes.','ES-006A','ES-008: Reporting and investigation of Accident, Incident, Near Miss or any kind of dangerous occurrence, N/A: Amneal Ireland Emergency Response Plan.'),(64,'ES-008B','REPORTING AND INVESTIGATION OF ACCIDENT, INCIDENT, NEAR MISS AND ANY KIND OF DANGEROUS OCCURRENCE','To establish a procedure for reporting and investigating accidents, incidents, near misses, and dangerous occurrences to ensure corrective and preventive actions are implemented, and adequate records are maintained.\n---\nThis SOP applies to all accidents, incidents, near misses, and EHS non-conformances occurring on company premises or while on company business elsewhere. GMP investigations are performed as per SOP QM-010.\n---\nThe procedure outlines the reporting and investigation of accidents, incidents, near misses, and dangerous occurrences. It includes steps for incident reporting, root cause analysis (RCA), corrective and preventive actions (CAPA), and communication of lessons learned.\n---\nES-008: 22-Dec-2016 - First Issued, ES-008A: 05-Dec-2019 - Updated to new template, ES-008B: cb - MN-3023 - Included EHS responsibility to report biological incidents, added definition of biological incident, and referenced European Directive 2000/54/EC.\n---\nEHS Department: Report and document incidents, ensure RCA completion, track CAPAs, and notify regulatory authorities. All Employees: Report incidents, follow medical advice, and cooperate in investigations. Emergency Response Team/First Aiders/Occupational Health: Provide first aid, refer to Occupational Health, and report injuries. Leadership Team: Ensure emergency response activation, RCA team establishment, and CAPA implementation.','ES-008B Reporting and investigation of accident, incident.pdf',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:02:54',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'To establish a procedure for reporting and investigating accidents, incidents, near misses, and dangerous occurrences to ensure corrective and preventive actions are implemented, and adequate records are maintained.','This SOP applies to all accidents, incidents, near misses, and EHS non-conformances occurring on company premises or while on company business elsewhere. GMP investigations are performed as per SOP QM-010.','The procedure outlines the reporting and investigation of accidents, incidents, near misses, and dangerous occurrences. It includes steps for incident reporting, root cause analysis (RCA), corrective and preventive actions (CAPA), and communication of lessons learned.','Amneal Ireland: Amneal Ireland Limited Cahir Road, Cashel, Co. Tipperary, Ireland, Affected Employees: Employees whose work or work areas could be affected by an incident or near miss, Causal Factor: Any factor contributing to the cause or severity of a hazard or failure, Controlled Substances: Substances requiring a license under the Misuse of Drugs Act, 1977, Co. Co.: County Council, CAPA: Corrective Action and/or Preventative Action, Dangerous Occurrence: An incident reportable to the HSA, EHS: Environmental, Health and Safety, Environmental Event: Any spill, release, or non-compliance with environmental regulations, EPA: Environmental Protection Agency, ERT: Emergency Response Team, First-Aid: One-time medical treatment for minor injuries, HSA: Health and Safety Authority, Illness: Non-traumatic physiological harm or loss of capacity, Incident: A work-related injury, illness, or significant event, Injury: A traumatic wound or condition caused by external forces, Irish Water: Water utility company in Ireland, Lost time Case: A nonfatal injury causing loss of time from work, Lost time Accident: Reportable to HSA if an employee cannot work for more than 3 consecutive days, Medical Treatment: Treatment administered by a physician, Notifiable Incident: An occurrence requiring notification to regulatory authorities, OH: Occupational Health, Potentially Affected Employees: Employees who could benefit from incident reports or corrective actions, Regulatory Authority: EPA, Tipperary County Council, HSA, Recordable Injury/Illness: Any work-related injury/illness requiring medical treatment beyond first aid, Root-Cause: The fundamental reason for a failure, SHWW: Safety, Health & Welfare at Work, Root Cause Analysis (RCA): A method of problem solving to identify root causes, Significant Event: EHS incidents requiring prompt reporting, Supervisor: Direct supervisor, Trend Analysis: The process of spotting patterns or trends, Work-related injury/illness: An injury or illness acquired or aggravated at work, Biological Incident: Unintended release or exposure to potentially infectious materials.','EHS Department: Report and document incidents, ensure RCA completion, track CAPAs, and notify regulatory authorities. All Employees: Report incidents, follow medical advice, and cooperate in investigations. Emergency Response Team/First Aiders/Occupational Health: Provide first aid, refer to Occupational Health, and report injuries. Leadership Team: Ensure emergency response activation, RCA team establishment, and CAPA implementation.','ES-008: 22-Dec-2016 - First Issued, ES-008A: 05-Dec-2019 - Updated to new template, ES-008B: cb - MN-3023 - Included EHS responsibility to report biological incidents, added definition of biological incident, and referenced European Directive 2000/54/EC.','ES-008A','FM-ES-009: Incident Investigation Form, FM-ES-010: 5-Why Worksheet, FM-ES-011: Incident Investigation Process Flow Diagram, N/A: Amneal Ireland Emergency Response Plan, FM-ES-008: Risk Assessment Form, QM-010: Investigation System, N/A: Local Government (Water Pollution) Acts 1977-1990, N/A: Radiological Protection Act of 1991, N/A: European Directive 2000/54/EC Biological Agents at Work.'),(65,'ES-009B','ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH & SAFETY RISK ASSESSMENT','To describe the procedure for effective risk assessment of work areas and activities at Amneal Ireland, ensuring adequate controls are in place to prevent harm.\n---\nThis procedure applies to machine and ancillary equipment and work-related activities conducted inside the Amneal Ireland facility.\n---\nThe procedure outlines the risk assessment process for work areas and activities at Amneal Ireland. It includes identifying hazards, assessing risks, and determining controls to prevent harm. Risks are prioritized using a scoring methodology, and control measures follow the hierarchy of controls.\n---\nES-009: 06-Apr-2016 - First Issued, ES-009A: 16-Apr-2020 - Updated to new Amneal logo, ES-009B: 04-Aug-2020 - Added reference to activities and contractors, updated definitions, and restructured tables.\n---\nEHS is responsible for maintaining the EHS Risk Register, documenting risk assessments, and ensuring CAPA’s are recorded. The risk assessment team composition depends on the scope of the assessment.','ES-009B EHS Risk Assessment.pdf',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:02:54',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'To describe the procedure for effective risk assessment of work areas and activities at Amneal Ireland, ensuring adequate controls are in place to prevent harm.','This procedure applies to machine and ancillary equipment and work-related activities conducted inside the Amneal Ireland facility.','The procedure outlines the risk assessment process for work areas and activities at Amneal Ireland. It includes identifying hazards, assessing risks, and determining controls to prevent harm. Risks are prioritized using a scoring methodology, and control measures follow the hierarchy of controls.','Hazard: A potential source of harm or adverse health effect, Risk: Likelihood of harm or adverse health effects, Controls: Actions to reduce exposure to hazards, CAPA’s: Corrective action and preventative actions, EHS: Environmental Health and Safety, Risk Assessment: Process of identifying hazards, assessing risks, and determining controls, LTA: Lost Time Accident, OEL: Occupational exposure level, Safety Hazard: Hazards creating unsafe working conditions, Chemical Hazard: Chemical agents classified as dangerous substances, Physical Hazard: Environmental factors that can harm without physical contact, Biological Hazard: Viruses, bacteria, fungi, etc., Ergonomic Hazard: Physical factors causing musculoskeletal injuries, Psychosocial Hazard: Hazards affecting mental health or wellbeing, Amneal Ireland: Amneal Ireland Limited, Cahir Road, Cashel, Co. Tipperary, Ireland.','EHS is responsible for maintaining the EHS Risk Register, documenting risk assessments, and ensuring CAPA’s are recorded. The risk assessment team composition depends on the scope of the assessment.','ES-009: 06-Apr-2016 - First Issued, ES-009A: 16-Apr-2020 - Updated to new Amneal logo, ES-009B: 04-Aug-2020 - Added reference to activities and contractors, updated definitions, and restructured tables.','ES-009A','FM-ES-008: EHS Risk Assessment Form'),(66,'ES-010E','MANAGEMENT OF CONTRACTORS','To describe the procedure for managing contractors at Amneal Ireland, ensuring compliance with EU/Irish legislation and site EHS procedures.\n---\nThis procedure applies to all contract companies and personnel performing specific physical activities at the facility, including building maintenance, equipment installation, and construction projects. It does not apply to embedded contractors, temporary staff, or visitors.\n---\nThe procedure outlines the management of contractors at Amneal Ireland, ensuring compliance with EU/Irish legislation and site EHS procedures. It includes contractor selection, documentation, permits, training, and incident management.\n---\nES-010: 04-Apr-2016 - First Issued, ES-010A: 20-Apr-2017 - Updated form references, ES-010B: 04-Jul-2017 - Updated definitions, ES-010C: 07-Feb-2018 - Updated form references and added points, ES-010D: 05-Feb-2020 - Updated to new Amneal logo, ES-010E: 13-Sep-2021 - Updated to include Covid-19 requirements, removed outdated references, and aligned with ISO 45001.\n---\nSite Contact: Manages and coordinates contractor work, ensures training and compliance. Contract Companies: Ensure contractor employees follow procedures. Security: Manages access control and induction. EHS: Manages the contractor management process and maintains the Approved Contractors List. QA: Assesses GMP impact and maintains documentation.','ES-010E Management of Contractors.pdf',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:02:54',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'To describe the procedure for managing contractors at Amneal Ireland, ensuring compliance with EU/Irish legislation and site EHS procedures.','This procedure applies to all contract companies and personnel performing specific physical activities at the facility, including building maintenance, equipment installation, and construction projects. It does not apply to embedded contractors, temporary staff, or visitors.','The procedure outlines the management of contractors at Amneal Ireland, ensuring compliance with EU/Irish legislation and site EHS procedures. It includes contractor selection, documentation, permits, training, and incident management.','Site Contact: Person responsible for the Contractor’s activity, Approved Contractors List (ACL): List of approved contractors, Contractor: Individual or firm retained on a temporary/contractual basis, Contractor EHS Qualification Form: Form completed by potential contractors, Contractor Personnel: Non-Amneal employees performing work, Visitor: Individual on site not performing physical work, Method Statement: Document detailing job safety, Risk Assessment: Process to identify and control hazards, cGMP: Current good manufacturing practice, CE Mark: Indicates compliance with EU safety requirements, AF2 form: Form for notifying HSA of construction activity, PAT: Portable appliance test, LOTO: Lockout/Tagout procedure, EHS: Environmental, Health and Safety, Amneal Ireland: Amneal Ireland Limited, Cahir Road, Cashel, Co. Tipperary, Ireland, ISO 14001: Environmental Management System standard, EMAS: Environmental Management and Audit Scheme, ISO 45001: Health and Safety Management System standard, Lost time cases: Non-fatal injury causing loss of work time, Restricted Workday case: Employee prevented from performing routine functions, Medical Attention Cases: Treatment beyond first aid.','Site Contact: Manages and coordinates contractor work, ensures training and compliance. Contract Companies: Ensure contractor employees follow procedures. Security: Manages access control and induction. EHS: Manages the contractor management process and maintains the Approved Contractors List. QA: Assesses GMP impact and maintains documentation.','ES-010: 04-Apr-2016 - First Issued, ES-010A: 20-Apr-2017 - Updated form references, ES-010B: 04-Jul-2017 - Updated definitions, ES-010C: 07-Feb-2018 - Updated form references and added points, ES-010D: 05-Feb-2020 - Updated to new Amneal logo, ES-010E: 13-Sep-2021 - Updated to include Covid-19 requirements, removed outdated references, and aligned with ISO 45001.','ES-010D','N/A: Safety, Health and Welfare at Work Act, 2005, Safety, Health and Welfare at Work (General Application) Regulations, 2007, Safety, Health and Welfare at Work (Construction) Regulations, 2013, FM-ES-004: Method Statement Risk Assessment, FM-ES-007: Approved Contractor List, FM-ES-003: Contractor EHS Qualification Form, N/A: Permit to Work Procedure, QA-006: Procurement and Approval of Miscellaneous Supplies, QM-044: Supplier Management and Control, QM-045: Covid-19 Pandemic GxP Practices, QRM-20: Good Manufacturing Practices related to Covid-19 Pandemic-01.'),(67,'FM-ES-009-02','Incident Investigation Form','To provide a structured format for documenting and investigating incidents, ensuring that corrective and preventive actions are identified and implemented.\n---\nThis form applies to all incidents, including injuries, environmental releases, and other potential incidents that occur on-site or during company business.\n---\nThe form is used to document and investigate incidents, including environmental or biological releases, injuries, and other potential incidents. It includes sections for incident details, injury details, environmental release information, root cause analysis (RCA), corrective and preventive actions (CAPA), and management review.\n---\nEHS Department: Responsible for reviewing and approving the incident investigation form. Site Management: Responsible for verifying that CAPAs are appropriate and sustainable. Incident Investigators: Responsible for completing the form and conducting the root cause analysis.','FM-ES-009-02 Incident investigation form.docx',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:02:54',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'To provide a structured format for documenting and investigating incidents, ensuring that corrective and preventive actions are identified and implemented.','This form applies to all incidents, including injuries, environmental releases, and other potential incidents that occur on-site or during company business.','The form is used to document and investigate incidents, including environmental or biological releases, injuries, and other potential incidents. It includes sections for incident details, injury details, environmental release information, root cause analysis (RCA), corrective and preventive actions (CAPA), and management review.',NULL,'EHS Department: Responsible for reviewing and approving the incident investigation form. Site Management: Responsible for verifying that CAPAs are appropriate and sustainable. Incident Investigators: Responsible for completing the form and conducting the root cause analysis.',NULL,NULL,NULL),(68,'FM-ES-010','5-Whys','To provide a structured approach for identifying the root cause of incidents or problems by asking \"Why?\" multiple times, leading to effective corrective actions.\n---\nThis worksheet applies to all incidents, problems, or non-conformances that require root cause analysis within the organization.\n---\nThe 5-Whys worksheet is a tool used for root cause analysis (RCA) to identify the underlying cause of a problem by repeatedly asking \"Why?\" until the root cause is determined. It helps in identifying corrective actions to prevent recurrence.\n---\nIncident Investigators: Responsible for completing the 5-Whys worksheet as part of the root cause analysis process. EHS Department: Responsible for reviewing and approving the analysis.','FM-ES-010 5-Whys.docx',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:02:54',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'To provide a structured approach for identifying the root cause of incidents or problems by asking \"Why?\" multiple times, leading to effective corrective actions.','This worksheet applies to all incidents, problems, or non-conformances that require root cause analysis within the organization.','The 5-Whys worksheet is a tool used for root cause analysis (RCA) to identify the underlying cause of a problem by repeatedly asking \"Why?\" until the root cause is determined. It helps in identifying corrective actions to prevent recurrence.',NULL,'Incident Investigators: Responsible for completing the 5-Whys worksheet as part of the root cause analysis process. EHS Department: Responsible for reviewing and approving the analysis.',NULL,NULL,NULL),(69,'FM-ES-010-00','Root Cause Analysis 5-Why Worksheet','To provide a structured approach for identifying the root cause of incidents or problems by asking \"Why?\" multiple times, leading to effective corrective actions.\n---\nThis worksheet applies to all incidents, problems, or non-conformances that require root cause analysis within the organization.\n---\nThe 5-Why Worksheet is a tool used for root cause analysis (RCA) to identify the underlying cause of a problem by repeatedly asking \"Why?\" until the root cause is determined. It helps in identifying corrective actions to prevent recurrence.\n---\nIncident Investigators: Responsible for completing the 5-Why Worksheet as part of the root cause analysis process. EHS Department: Responsible for reviewing and approving the analysis.','FM-ES-010-00 Root Cause Analysis 5-why Worksheet.doc',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:02:54',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'To provide a structured approach for identifying the root cause of incidents or problems by asking \"Why?\" multiple times, leading to effective corrective actions.','This worksheet applies to all incidents, problems, or non-conformances that require root cause analysis within the organization.','The 5-Why Worksheet is a tool used for root cause analysis (RCA) to identify the underlying cause of a problem by repeatedly asking \"Why?\" until the root cause is determined. It helps in identifying corrective actions to prevent recurrence.',NULL,'Incident Investigators: Responsible for completing the 5-Why Worksheet as part of the root cause analysis process. EHS Department: Responsible for reviewing and approving the analysis.',NULL,NULL,NULL),(70,'FM-ES-011-00','Incident Investigation Process Flow Diagram','To outline the process for investigating incidents, ensuring a structured and consistent approach to identifying root causes and implementing corrective actions.\n---\nThis flow diagram applies to all incidents, including injuries, environmental releases, and other potential incidents that occur on-site or during company business.\n---\nThe Incident Investigation Process Flow Diagram provides a visual representation of the steps involved in investigating incidents, including securing the scene, notifying relevant authorities, conducting the investigation, and implementing corrective actions.\n---\nEHS Department: Responsible for overseeing the incident investigation process. Incident Investigators: Responsible for following the flow diagram during investigations. Site Management: Responsible for reviewing and approving corrective actions.','FM-ES-011-00 Incident Investigation Process Flow Diagram.doc',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:02:54',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'To outline the process for investigating incidents, ensuring a structured and consistent approach to identifying root causes and implementing corrective actions.','This flow diagram applies to all incidents, including injuries, environmental releases, and other potential incidents that occur on-site or during company business.','The Incident Investigation Process Flow Diagram provides a visual representation of the steps involved in investigating incidents, including securing the scene, notifying relevant authorities, conducting the investigation, and implementing corrective actions.',NULL,'EHS Department: Responsible for overseeing the incident investigation process. Incident Investigators: Responsible for following the flow diagram during investigations. Site Management: Responsible for reviewing and approving corrective actions.',NULL,NULL,NULL),(71,'QC-007C','CONTACT PLATE SAMPLING','To describe the steps needed for Contact Plate sampling at Amneal Ireland. This can also be referred to as Surface Plate sampling.\n---\nThe scope of this SOP is limited to the set-up, operation, and handling of the Contact Plates during sampling. Contact Plate sampling is used in Amneal Ireland to detect microorganisms on surfaces that could lead to product contamination.\n---\nContact Plate sampling is used to detect microorganisms on surfaces that could lead to product contamination. The procedure includes set-up, operation, and handling of Contact Plates during sampling.\n---\nQC-007: First Issued on 25-May-2016. QC-007A: Updated on 14-Apr-2017. QC-007B: Updated on 29-Nov-2018. QC-007C: Updated on 08-Nov-2021.\n---\nIt is the responsibility of all personnel completing Contact Plate sampling to adhere to this SOP. It is the responsibility of Environmental Monitoring Samplers (QA, QC/ARD, Operations) to contact manufacturing and to liaise with the planner prior to performing environmental monitoring sampling.','QC-007C Contact Plate Sampling.pdf',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:03:44',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'To describe the steps needed for Contact Plate sampling at Amneal Ireland. This can also be referred to as Surface Plate sampling.','The scope of this SOP is limited to the set-up, operation, and handling of the Contact Plates during sampling. Contact Plate sampling is used in Amneal Ireland to detect microorganisms on surfaces that could lead to product contamination.','Contact Plate sampling is used to detect microorganisms on surfaces that could lead to product contamination. The procedure includes set-up, operation, and handling of Contact Plates during sampling.','IPA – Iso Propyl Alcohol, QC – Quality Control, TSA – Tryptic Soya Agar, QC/ARD – Quality/ Analytical Research and Development/Microbiology, QA – Quality Assurance, SOP - Standard Operating Procedure, Amneal Ireland: Amneal Ireland Limited Cahir Road, Cashel, Co. Tipperary, Ireland.','It is the responsibility of all personnel completing Contact Plate sampling to adhere to this SOP. It is the responsibility of Environmental Monitoring Samplers (QA, QC/ARD, Operations) to contact manufacturing and to liaise with the planner prior to performing environmental monitoring sampling.','QC-007: First Issued on 25-May-2016. QC-007A: Updated on 14-Apr-2017. QC-007B: Updated on 29-Nov-2018. QC-007C: Updated on 08-Nov-2021.','QC-007B','QC-011: Routine Microbiological Environmental Monitoring, QC-075: Environmental Monitoring Sampling and Incubation Procedure, ES-001: Material Destruction and Waste Management Procedure.'),(72,'QC-008E','OPERATION, CALIBRATION AND MAINTENANCE OF KARL FISCHER TITRATOR (METROHM 851 TITRANDO)','To define the procedure for the operation, calibration, and maintenance of Karl Fischer Titrator (Metrohm 851 Titrando).\n---\nThis procedure applies to the Quality Control and Analytical Research & Development (QC/ARD) Laboratory at Amneal, Ireland.\n---\nThe procedure includes pre-use checks, cleaning, conditioning, calibration, sample analysis, and maintenance of the Karl Fischer Titrator. Calibration must be performed prior to sample analysis, and maintenance activities are documented in the Karl Fischer Usage and Maintenance Logbook.\n---\nQC-008: First Issued on 09-Sep-2016. QC-008A: Updated on 23-Aug-2018. QC-008B: Updated on 10-Dec-2018. QC-008C: Updated on 27-Jul-2020. QC-008D: Updated on 20-Oct-2020. QC-008E: Updated on 23-Jul-2021.\n---\nThe Laboratory personnel shall follow the instructions in this procedure. The Laboratory Manager is responsible for ensuring that Laboratory personnel comply with this procedure.','QC-008E Operation Calibration Maintenance of Karl Fischer Titrator.pdf',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:03:44',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'To define the procedure for the operation, calibration, and maintenance of Karl Fischer Titrator (Metrohm 851 Titrando).','This procedure applies to the Quality Control and Analytical Research & Development (QC/ARD) Laboratory at Amneal, Ireland.','The procedure includes pre-use checks, cleaning, conditioning, calibration, sample analysis, and maintenance of the Karl Fischer Titrator. Calibration must be performed prior to sample analysis, and maintenance activities are documented in the Karl Fischer Usage and Maintenance Logbook.','Amneal Ireland: Amneal Ireland Limited, Cahir Road, Cashel, Co. Tipperary, Ireland. RSD: Relative Standard Deviation. NMT: Not More Than. Tiamo: Tiamo 2.5 multi software.','The Laboratory personnel shall follow the instructions in this procedure. The Laboratory Manager is responsible for ensuring that Laboratory personnel comply with this procedure.','QC-008: First Issued on 09-Sep-2016. QC-008A: Updated on 23-Aug-2018. QC-008B: Updated on 10-Dec-2018. QC-008C: Updated on 27-Jul-2020. QC-008D: Updated on 20-Oct-2020. QC-008E: Updated on 23-Jul-2021.','QC-008D','Karl Fischer Calibration Form (FM-QC-003), Karl Fischer Usage and Maintenance Logbook (FM-QC-004), SOP QC-082: Operational use of Tiamo software, SOP QC-022: Control of Laboratory Instruments.'),(73,'QC-009I','RECEIPT AND HANDLING OF INCOMING SAMPLES IN THE QC/ARD AND MICROBIOLOGY LABORATORY','To provide a procedure for the submission, receipt and handling of all samples submitted to the Quality Control / Analytical Research & Development Laboratory and to the Quality Control / Analytical Research and Development Microbiology Laboratory.\n---\nThis procedure applies to the submission, receipt and handling of all samples (i.e. raw materials, packaging materials, in process, finished product, stability, cleaning and other samples) received in the QC/ARD Laboratory at Amneal, Ireland. This procedure also applies to the submission, receipt and handling of all samples (i.e. EM, media plates, consumables and other samples) received in the QC/ARD Microbiology Laboratory at Amneal Ireland. Retain (Reference /Retention) samples are outside the scope of this SOP and are covered by SOP QM-027.\n---\nSample submission, receipt verification, sample identification, sample storage, sample disposal, external laboratory handling, reporting of results, monthly review.\n---\nQC-009: 28-Sep-2016 - First Issued. QC-009A: 20-Dec-2017 - Updated to include handling of all samples, removed duplication, added definitions. QC-009B: 26-Oct-2018 - Updated title, included Microbiology Laboratory, clarified sample identification format. QC-009C: 16-May-2019 - Updated template, added new sections. QC-009D: 20-Jun-2020 - Included submission and receipt, updated sample identification formats. QC-009E: 22-Jun-2020 - Added monthly sample receipt check. QC-009F: 16-Nov-2021 - Updated DPI content uniformity sample submission. QC-009G: 26-Apr-2022 - Updated sample identification for development samples. QC-009H: 22-Nov-2022 - Added documentation for sample removal. QC-009I: 03-Apr-2023 - Added sample inspection instructions.\n---\nPersonnel involved in the submission and handling of samples shall comply with the requirements of this procedure and ensure that they are trained to the current version of this procedure. QC/ARD personnel or designee involved in the receipt and handling of incoming samples shall comply with the requirements of this procedure and must ensure that they are trained to the current version of this procedure. Laboratory Manager or designee must ensure that all personnel performing the steps outlined in this procedure are appropriately trained.','QC-009I Receipt & Handling of incoming samples in QC-Micro Lab.pdf',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:03:44',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'To provide a procedure for the submission, receipt and handling of all samples submitted to the Quality Control / Analytical Research & Development Laboratory and to the Quality Control / Analytical Research and Development Microbiology Laboratory.','This procedure applies to the submission, receipt and handling of all samples (i.e. raw materials, packaging materials, in process, finished product, stability, cleaning and other samples) received in the QC/ARD Laboratory at Amneal, Ireland. This procedure also applies to the submission, receipt and handling of all samples (i.e. EM, media plates, consumables and other samples) received in the QC/ARD Microbiology Laboratory at Amneal Ireland. Retain (Reference /Retention) samples are outside the scope of this SOP and are covered by SOP QM-027.','Sample submission, receipt verification, sample identification, sample storage, sample disposal, external laboratory handling, reporting of results, monthly review.','Amneal Ireland: Amneal Ireland Limited Cahir Road, Cashel, Co. Tipperary, Ireland. COA: Certificate of Analysis. Non-cleaning samples: Samples other than Cleaning Validation/Verification Samples. CL: Cleaning. EM: Environmental Monitoring. QC/ARD: Quality Control/Analytical Research and Development. ID: Identification. CVR: Cleaning Validation Report. Approved Document: Data entry documents approved for recording the execution of an analytical method e.g. bound logbooks, bound notebooks, Laboratory analytical worksheets (LAWs). LAW: Laboratory Analytical Worksheet.','Personnel involved in the submission and handling of samples shall comply with the requirements of this procedure and ensure that they are trained to the current version of this procedure. QC/ARD personnel or designee involved in the receipt and handling of incoming samples shall comply with the requirements of this procedure and must ensure that they are trained to the current version of this procedure. Laboratory Manager or designee must ensure that all personnel performing the steps outlined in this procedure are appropriately trained.','QC-009: 28-Sep-2016 - First Issued. QC-009A: 20-Dec-2017 - Updated to include handling of all samples, removed duplication, added definitions. QC-009B: 26-Oct-2018 - Updated title, included Microbiology Laboratory, clarified sample identification format. QC-009C: 16-May-2019 - Updated template, added new sections. QC-009D: 20-Jun-2020 - Included submission and receipt, updated sample identification formats. QC-009E: 22-Jun-2020 - Added monthly sample receipt check. QC-009F: 16-Nov-2021 - Updated DPI content uniformity sample submission. QC-009G: 26-Apr-2022 - Updated sample identification for development samples. QC-009H: 22-Nov-2022 - Added documentation for sample removal. QC-009I: 03-Apr-2023 - Added sample inspection instructions.','QC-009H','FM-QC-005: Sample Receipt Logbook. QM-027: Retention Sample Management. FM-MF-034: Sample Test Request Form. MF-042: Procedure for Sample Movement/Management. MF-020: Product Development Sample Analysis Request. MM-011: Courier Shipments. QC-011: Routine Microbiological Environmental Monitoring. QC-074: Environmental Monitoring Reading and Reporting Procedure. QC-075: Environmental Monitoring Sampling and Incubation Procedure. QC-010: Recording and Reporting of Laboratory Test Data. QC-028: Sample Transfer to Global Amneal Sites. ES-001: Material Destruction and Waste Management Procedure. FM-QC-196: QC/ARD Sample Receipt Log. FM-QC-195: QC/ARD Cleaning Sample Receipt Log. FM-MF-032: Sample Label. FM-QC-039: QC/ARD Test Request Form. MF-086: Operation of RF-Smart Labelling. QC-043: Release of Results from QC-ARD. FM-MF-026: Sample for Analysis label. FM-QC-257: Sample Receipt Monthly Review Logbook. FM-QC-283: QC/ARD Development Sample Receipt Log.'),(74,'QC-010H','RECORDING AND REPORTING OF LABORATORY TEST DATA','To describe the procedure for the recording and reporting of data in the QC/ARD laboratory to assure the integrity of all laboratory data is maintained. To describe the procedure for documenting and reporting Microbiology Results.\n---\nThis procedure applies to all personnel in the Quality Control and Analytical Research & Development (QC/ARD)/Microbiology department at Amneal, Ireland.\n---\nRecording and reporting of laboratory test data, handling of raw data, rounding analytical data, use of Laboratory Analytical Worksheets (LAWs), handling of microbiology results, and monthly review of laboratory records.\n---\nQC-010: 30-Sep-2016 - First Issued. QC-010A: 21-Dec-2017 - Updated to include handling of all samples, removed duplication, added definitions. QC-010B: 28-Feb-2019 - Updated procedure to new template, updated Amneal logo, added sections for Microbiology. QC-010C: 15-May-2019 - Updated responsibilities, clarified sample identification formats. QC-010D: 30-Jul-2020 - Clarified sample handling and reporting procedures. QC-010E: 12-Mar-2021 - Updated LAW formats and added new sections. QC-010F: 06-Sep-2021 - Updated diluent handling precautions. QC-010G: 29-Sep-2021 - Updated Approved Document definition and added new sections. QC-010H: 24-Jun-2022 - Added new sections for sample inspection and updated LAW formats.\n---\nLaboratory personnel shall comply with the requirements of this procedure. Laboratory Manager or designee shall ensure that the steps outlined in this procedure are followed. Laboratory Manager or designee must ensure that all personnel performing the steps outlined in this procedure are appropriately trained. Laboratory personnel is responsible for printing the current version of the LAW from the designated controlled location. Laboratory manager or designee shall be responsible for assigning a unique Laboratory Analytical Worksheets prior to use. QA Document Control are responsible for issuance of approved bound logbooks/notebooks upon request.','QC-010H Recording Reporting of Lab Test Data.pdf',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:03:44',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'To describe the procedure for the recording and reporting of data in the QC/ARD laboratory to assure the integrity of all laboratory data is maintained. To describe the procedure for documenting and reporting Microbiology Results.','This procedure applies to all personnel in the Quality Control and Analytical Research & Development (QC/ARD)/Microbiology department at Amneal, Ireland.','Recording and reporting of laboratory test data, handling of raw data, rounding analytical data, use of Laboratory Analytical Worksheets (LAWs), handling of microbiology results, and monthly review of laboratory records.','Raw Data: Original records and documentation retained in the format in which they were originally generated. Final test result: Result reported on the Certificate of Analysis. Approved Document: Data entry documents approved for recording the execution of an analytical method. Decimal place: Position of a digit to the right of a decimal point. Significant figure: Any digit of a number that is known with certainty. Amneal Ireland: Amneal Ireland Limited Cahir Road, Cashel, Co. Tipperary, Ireland. TRSF: Test Request Submission Form. Contract Laboratory Requirement (CLR): Document detailing the procedure and specifications for a validated Test Method. C of A: Certificate of Analysis. Data Integrity: Completeness, consistency, and accuracy of data. UD: Unplanned Deviation. NOE: Notification of Event.','Laboratory personnel shall comply with the requirements of this procedure. Laboratory Manager or designee shall ensure that the steps outlined in this procedure are followed. Laboratory Manager or designee must ensure that all personnel performing the steps outlined in this procedure are appropriately trained. Laboratory personnel is responsible for printing the current version of the LAW from the designated controlled location. Laboratory manager or designee shall be responsible for assigning a unique Laboratory Analytical Worksheets prior to use. QA Document Control are responsible for issuance of approved bound logbooks/notebooks upon request.','QC-010: 30-Sep-2016 - First Issued. QC-010A: 21-Dec-2017 - Updated to include handling of all samples, removed duplication, added definitions. QC-010B: 28-Feb-2019 - Updated procedure to new template, updated Amneal logo, added sections for Microbiology. QC-010C: 15-May-2019 - Updated responsibilities, clarified sample identification formats. QC-010D: 30-Jul-2020 - Clarified sample handling and reporting procedures. QC-010E: 12-Mar-2021 - Updated LAW formats and added new sections. QC-010F: 06-Sep-2021 - Updated diluent handling precautions. QC-010G: 29-Sep-2021 - Updated Approved Document definition and added new sections. QC-010H: 24-Jun-2022 - Added new sections for sample inspection and updated LAW formats.','QC-010G','FM-QC-006: Guideline for reporting test results. FM-QC-108: Microbiological impact assessment of an atypical growth result found during FP testing for organisms of concern. FM-QC-109: Log of Microbiological impact assessment numbers. FM-QC-203: Assignment of LAW numbers logbook. FM-QC-204: Laboratory Analytical Data Pack Cover Page. FM-QC-205: 1298-AS LAW for Blend Uniformity and Blend Assay. FM-QC-206: 1298-AS LAW Blister Content Uniformity and Assay. FM-QC-207: 1298-CL LAW for Cleaning Verification. FM-QC-208: 1298-WC LAW for Water Content. FM-QC-209: 1298-APSD LAW for Aerodynamic Particle Size Distribution. FM-QC-210: 1290-AL LAW for Alcohol Content. FM-QC-211: 1290-CL LAW for Cleaning Verification. FM-QC-212: 1290-AS LAW for Assay. FM-QC-213: 1290-KF LAW for Water Content. FM-QC-214: 1291-AL LAW for Alcohol Content. FM-QC-215: 1291-AS LAW for Assay. FM-QC-216: 1291-KF LAW for Water Content. FM-QC-217: 1291-CL LAW for Cleaning Verification. FM-QC-218: MDI-GM LAW for General Method for Description. FM-QC-219: LQ-CL LAW for Cleaning Verification. FM-QC-260: 1614-CL LAW for Cleaning Verification. FM-QC-261: LAW for General Tests. FM-QC-262: 1614-AS LAW for Assay. FM-QC-263: 1614-WC LAW for Water Content. SOP QM-004: Good Documentation Practices. SOP QA-001: Procedure for Document Issuance. SOP QM-009: Document Storage and Retention. SOP QC-001: Investigation of Out of specification (OOS) laboratory results. SOP QC-006: Review of Laboratory records. SOP QM-010: Unplanned Deviations and Investigation System. SOP QC-034: Management of QC/ARD specifications, analytical methods (procedures) and method transfer protocols. SOP QC-049: Notification of event from contract laboratories to Amneal Ireland. SOP QC-083: Handling of Microbiology Out of Specifications (OOS) Results. SOP QM-013: Change Control System. SOP QM-024: Management of Electronic Forms. SOP QC-028: Sample Transfer to Global Amneal Sites. SOP QM-036: Data Integrity and Records Management. SOP QC-085: Investigation of atypical results reported in QC Lab. FM-QC-253: 01-1623-AS LAW for Assay. FM-QC-254: 01-1623-RC LAW for Related Compounds. FM-QC-255: 01-1623-RS LAW for Residual Solvents. FM-QC-291: LAW for additional pages.'),(75,'QC-011K','ROUTINE MICROBIOLOGICAL ENVIRONMENTAL MONITORING','To describe the procedure for performing Microbiological Environmental Monitoring (EM) of the MDI and DPI Inhalation Facility.\n---\nThis procedure applies to Viable Environmental Monitoring of the Inhalation Facility at Amneal Ireland. Environmental monitoring is performed within the ISO 7 and ISO 8 classified areas and selected CNC area (XP-35) in the Inhalation facility.\n---\nProcedure for performing Microbiological Environmental Monitoring (EM) of the MDI and DPI Inhalation Facility. Includes safety, methodology, frequency, sampling requirements, incubation conditions, acceptance criteria, failure handling, and trending of results.\n---\nQC-011 (08-Jul-2016): First Issued. QC-011A (24-Jan-2017): Added incubation details. QC-011B (14-Apr-2017): Updated scope and responsibilities. QC-011C (28-Jun-2017): Added DPI references. QC-011D (09-Oct-2017): Added definitions for Adverse Trends and Potential Organism of Concern. QC-011E (21-Dec-2017): Updated responsibilities and sampling details. QC-011F (14-Sep-2018): Updated sampling and monitoring details. QC-011G (26-Oct-2018): Updated responsibilities and definitions. QC-011H (12-Oct-2021): Updated titles and investigation details. QC-011I (30-Mar-2022): Included CNC XP-35 area and updated monitoring details. QC-011J (30-Mar-2022): Updated titles and investigation details.\n---\nEnvironmental Monitoring Samplers (QA, QC/ARD, Operations) are responsible for sampling. QC/ARD Microbiology personnel handle sample receipt, incubation, reading, and reporting. They also perform colony morphology analysis, streaking, and gram staining. The approved Contract Laboratory is responsible for organism identification and data reporting.','QC-011K Routine Microbiological EM.pdf',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:03:44',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'To describe the procedure for performing Microbiological Environmental Monitoring (EM) of the MDI and DPI Inhalation Facility.','This procedure applies to Viable Environmental Monitoring of the Inhalation Facility at Amneal Ireland. Environmental monitoring is performed within the ISO 7 and ISO 8 classified areas and selected CNC area (XP-35) in the Inhalation facility.','Procedure for performing Microbiological Environmental Monitoring (EM) of the MDI and DPI Inhalation Facility. Includes safety, methodology, frequency, sampling requirements, incubation conditions, acceptance criteria, failure handling, and trending of results.','At Rest/Static, In Operation/Dynamic, CFU, EM, ISO, MDI, MAS, VAS, QA, QC/ARD, OOS, TSA, DPI, QMS, SOP, HVAC, PPE, NMT, QP, PD, Alert Limit, Action Limit, Specification Limit, Adverse trend, Potential Organism of Concern, Amneal Ireland, CNC','Environmental Monitoring Samplers (QA, QC/ARD, Operations) are responsible for sampling. QC/ARD Microbiology personnel handle sample receipt, incubation, reading, and reporting. They also perform colony morphology analysis, streaking, and gram staining. The approved Contract Laboratory is responsible for organism identification and data reporting.','QC-011 (08-Jul-2016): First Issued. QC-011A (24-Jan-2017): Added incubation details. QC-011B (14-Apr-2017): Updated scope and responsibilities. QC-011C (28-Jun-2017): Added DPI references. QC-011D (09-Oct-2017): Added definitions for Adverse Trends and Potential Organism of Concern. QC-011E (21-Dec-2017): Updated responsibilities and sampling details. QC-011F (14-Sep-2018): Updated sampling and monitoring details. QC-011G (26-Oct-2018): Updated responsibilities and definitions. QC-011H (12-Oct-2021): Updated titles and investigation details. QC-011I (30-Mar-2022): Included CNC XP-35 area and updated monitoring details. QC-011J (30-Mar-2022): Updated titles and investigation details.','QC-011J','FM-QC-097, FM-QC-187, FM-QC-188, QC-003, QC-007, QC-004, MF-009, QM-010, QM-013, QC-049, QC-074, QC-075, QC-079, EudraLex, QM-019, MF-007, FM-QC-198, QC-086'),(76,'QC-012B','CHROMATOGRAPHIC COLUMN MANAGEMENT','To describe the procedure for managing chromatographic columns in the QC/AR&D Laboratory.\n---\nThis procedure applies to the management of HPLC, UPLC, and GC columns in the QC/AR&D Laboratory at Amneal Ireland.\n---\nProcedure for managing chromatographic columns in the QC/AR&D Laboratory. Includes column identification, usage logging, storage, cleaning, and disposal.\n---\nQC-012 (09-Sep-2016): First Issue. QC-012A (20-Aug-2019): Updated SOP and FM-QC-008 to new format. Removed reference to Appendix and specific facility. QC-012B (CC-AMN-23-2555): Updated Form FM-QC-008 to record column receipt activity separately from usage activity. Added new Form FM-QC-298 for column usage logging.\n---\nQC/AR&D Laboratory personnel are responsible for column identification, usage logging, storage, cleaning, and disposal.','QC-012B Chromatographic Column Mgt in the Quality Control Laboratory.pdf',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:03:44',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'To describe the procedure for managing chromatographic columns in the QC/AR&D Laboratory.','This procedure applies to the management of HPLC, UPLC, and GC columns in the QC/AR&D Laboratory at Amneal Ireland.','Procedure for managing chromatographic columns in the QC/AR&D Laboratory. Includes column identification, usage logging, storage, cleaning, and disposal.',NULL,'QC/AR&D Laboratory personnel are responsible for column identification, usage logging, storage, cleaning, and disposal.','QC-012 (09-Sep-2016): First Issue. QC-012A (20-Aug-2019): Updated SOP and FM-QC-008 to new format. Removed reference to Appendix and specific facility. QC-012B (CC-AMN-23-2555): Updated Form FM-QC-008 to record column receipt activity separately from usage activity. Added new Form FM-QC-298 for column usage logging.','QC-012A','FM-QC-008: Column receipt Logbook. FM-QC-298: Column usage logbook.'),(77,'QC-013B','OPERATION, CALIBRATION AND MAINTENANCE OF THE METTLER TOLEDO SEVENCOMPACT pH METER AND SENSOR','To define the operation, calibration, and maintenance of the Mettler Toledo SevenCompact pH meter and sensor.\n---\nThis procedure applies to the use of the Mettler Toledo SevenCompact pH meter and sensor by all QC/ARD personnel at Amneal Ireland.\n---\n1. Two display modes: full information screen and measurement close-up screen.\n2. Daily calibration required before use.\n3. Three-point calibration using pH buffers 2.00, 4.00, and 7.00.\n4. Maintenance includes keeping the meter clean and ensuring the electrode is properly stored and filled.\n---\n1. QC-013: First Issued on 03-Oct-2016.\n2. QC-013A: Updated SOP logo and removed reference to Appendix on 12-Sep-2019.\n3. QC-013B: Updated sections 5.2.1, 5.2.4, 5.3, and 5.3.9 on 01-Jul-2020.\n---\n1. All personnel using the instrument must adhere to this procedure.\n2. The Laboratory Manager (or designee) is responsible for ensuring the procedure is followed.\n3. Any problems encountered must be reported immediately to the Laboratory Manager (or designee).\n4. Personnel must be trained to the current revision of this document.','QC-013B Op, Cal & Maintenance of the pH Meter and Sensor.pdf',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:03:44',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'To define the operation, calibration, and maintenance of the Mettler Toledo SevenCompact pH meter and sensor.','This procedure applies to the use of the Mettler Toledo SevenCompact pH meter and sensor by all QC/ARD personnel at Amneal Ireland.','1. Two display modes: full information screen and measurement close-up screen.\n2. Daily calibration required before use.\n3. Three-point calibration using pH buffers 2.00, 4.00, and 7.00.\n4. Maintenance includes keeping the meter clean and ensuring the electrode is properly stored and filled.','1. pH: negative decimal reciprocal log of the hydrogen ion activity of a solution.\n2. LabX: proprietary Mettler software.\n3. ATC: automatic temperature control.\n4. MTC: manual temperature control.\n5. Amneal Ireland: Amneal Ireland Limited Cahir Road, Cashel, Co. Tipperary, Ireland.','1. All personnel using the instrument must adhere to this procedure.\n2. The Laboratory Manager (or designee) is responsible for ensuring the procedure is followed.\n3. Any problems encountered must be reported immediately to the Laboratory Manager (or designee).\n4. Personnel must be trained to the current revision of this document.','1. QC-013: First Issued on 03-Oct-2016.\n2. QC-013A: Updated SOP logo and removed reference to Appendix on 12-Sep-2019.\n3. QC-013B: Updated sections 5.2.1, 5.2.4, 5.3, and 5.3.9 on 01-Jul-2020.','QC-013A','1. FM-QC-011: pH instrument calibration logbook form.\n2. FM-QC-010: pH meter maintenance and usage logbook form.\n3. United States Pharmacopeia General Chapter <791>.'),(78,'QC-014A','OPERATION AND MAINTENANCE OF DESICCATOR','To define the operation and maintenance of Desiccators in the Quality Control and Analytical Research & Development (QC/ARD) Laboratory.\n---\nThis procedure applies to the use of Desiccators by all Laboratory personnel at Amneal, Ireland.\n---\n1. Reference standards stored in the Desiccator must be logged in the Incoming Reference Standards Logbook (FM-QC-015).\n2. Desiccators contain dry desiccant (e.g., silica gel) to minimize moisture exposure.\n3. Desiccators must be monitored monthly with a Hygrometer.\n4. Desiccant should be replaced when % relative humidity exceeds 40% or if the desiccant colour changes.\n---\n1. QC-014: First Issued on 29-Sep-2016.\n2. QC-014A: Updated SOP format, included reference to FM-QC-015, and updated monitoring frequency to monthly.\n---\n1. All Laboratory personnel must follow the instructions in this procedure.\n2. The Laboratory Manager is responsible for ensuring the procedure is adhered to.','QC-014A Operation & Maintenance of Dessicator (2).pdf',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:03:44',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'To define the operation and maintenance of Desiccators in the Quality Control and Analytical Research & Development (QC/ARD) Laboratory.','This procedure applies to the use of Desiccators by all Laboratory personnel at Amneal, Ireland.','1. Reference standards stored in the Desiccator must be logged in the Incoming Reference Standards Logbook (FM-QC-015).\n2. Desiccators contain dry desiccant (e.g., silica gel) to minimize moisture exposure.\n3. Desiccators must be monitored monthly with a Hygrometer.\n4. Desiccant should be replaced when % relative humidity exceeds 40% or if the desiccant colour changes.','1. Amneal Ireland: Amneal Ireland Limited Cahir Road, Cashel, Co. Tipperary, Ireland.','1. All Laboratory personnel must follow the instructions in this procedure.\n2. The Laboratory Manager is responsible for ensuring the procedure is adhered to.','1. QC-014: First Issued on 29-Sep-2016.\n2. QC-014A: Updated SOP format, included reference to FM-QC-015, and updated monitoring frequency to monthly.','QC-014','1. FM-QC-012: Desiccator Monitoring and Maintenance Logbook.\n2. FM-QC-015: Incoming Reference Standards Logbook.'),(79,'QC-015E','THE RECEIPT, PREPARATION, STORAGE, LABELLING AND EXPIRATION OF STANDARDS, REAGENTS AND SOLVENTS','To outline the steps for receiving, preparing, storing, labelling, and assigning expiry dates to reagents, solutions, and solvents within QC/ARD at Amneal Ireland.\n---\nThis procedure applies to all solutions prepared in QC/ARD at Amneal Ireland and their subsequent handling.\n---\n1. All lab personnel must read and understand SDS for chemicals and use correct PPE.\n2. Chemicals, standards, reagents, and solvents must be labelled with details such as chemical name, date of receipt, expiry date, and storage conditions.\n3. Solutions must be prepared in a fume hood and stored in designated areas.\n4. Expired solutions and reagents must be disposed of following SOP ES-001.\n5. Solutions must be visually checked for integrity before use.\n---\n1. QC-015: First Issued on 30-Sep-2016.\n2. QC-015A: Updated on 27-Jul-2018 to include PPE definition and safety steps.\n3. QC-015B: Updated on 07-Aug-2019 to remove references to appendices and update labelling requirements.\n4. QC-015C: Updated on 14-Jan-2020 to correct typographical errors and include analytical procedure version numbers.\n5. QC-015D: Updated on 27-May-2020 to include best practices for weighing and preparing solutions.\n6. QC-015E: Updated on 05-May-2020 to include monthly standard review checks.\n---\n1. All personnel within QC/ARD must adhere to this procedure.\n2. The Laboratory Manager or designee is responsible for ensuring the procedure is followed.','QC-015E Receipt Prep Storage Label & Exp of Reagent Solutions.pdf',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:03:44',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'To outline the steps for receiving, preparing, storing, labelling, and assigning expiry dates to reagents, solutions, and solvents within QC/ARD at Amneal Ireland.','This procedure applies to all solutions prepared in QC/ARD at Amneal Ireland and their subsequent handling.','1. All lab personnel must read and understand SDS for chemicals and use correct PPE.\n2. Chemicals, standards, reagents, and solvents must be labelled with details such as chemical name, date of receipt, expiry date, and storage conditions.\n3. Solutions must be prepared in a fume hood and stored in designated areas.\n4. Expired solutions and reagents must be disposed of following SOP ES-001.\n5. Solutions must be visually checked for integrity before use.','1. Standardized Solutions: Solutions of known concentration for quantitative determinations.\n2. Test Solutions and Indicators: Solutions of definitive concentrations for specific purposes.\n3. Indicators: Reagents used to determine end points in chemical reactions.\n4. Buffers: Solutions that resist changes in pH.\n5. Sample Solutions: Solutions prepared from test samples for analytical determinations.\n6. Standard Solutions: Solutions prepared from reference standards for quantitative determination.\n7. COA: Certificate of Analysis.\n8. Amneal Ireland: Amneal Ireland Limited Cahir Road, Cashel, Co. Tipperary, Ireland.\n9. QC: Quality Control.\n10. ARD: Analytical Research and Development.\n11. SDS: Safety Data Sheet.\n12. PPE: Personal Protective Equipment.','1. All personnel within QC/ARD must adhere to this procedure.\n2. The Laboratory Manager or designee is responsible for ensuring the procedure is followed.','1. QC-015: First Issued on 30-Sep-2016.\n2. QC-015A: Updated on 27-Jul-2018 to include PPE definition and safety steps.\n3. QC-015B: Updated on 07-Aug-2019 to remove references to appendices and update labelling requirements.\n4. QC-015C: Updated on 14-Jan-2020 to correct typographical errors and include analytical procedure version numbers.\n5. QC-015D: Updated on 27-May-2020 to include best practices for weighing and preparing solutions.\n6. QC-015E: Updated on 05-May-2020 to include monthly standard review checks.','QC-015D','1. FM-QC-009: Laboratory Chemical Register Log.\n2. FM-QC-014: Laboratory Solutions Preparation Log.\n3. FM-QC-126: Seal Wash Preparation Log.\n4. FM-QC-127: Needle Wash Preparation Log.\n5. FM-QC-128: Diluent 1298-AS/1298-CL/1298-APSD Preparation Log.\n6. FM-QC-129: Standard Solution 1298-AS Preparation Log.\n7. FM-QC-130: Standard Solution 1298-CL Preparation Log.\n8. FM-QC-131: Buffer 1298-AS/1298-CL/1298-APSD Preparation Log.\n9. FM-QC-132: Mobile Phase 1298-AS/1298-APSD Preparation Log.\n10. FM-QC-133: Mobile Phase 1298-CL Preparation Log.\n11. FM-QC-134: Standard LQ-CL Preparation Log.\n12. FM-QC-135: Standard Solution 1298-APSD Preparation Log.\n13. FM-QC-231: Laboratory Chemical Register Monthly Review Log.\n14. FM-QC-233: Diluent 1290-AS Preparation Log.\n15. FM-QC-234: Diluent 1290-CL Preparation Log.\n16. FM-QC-236: Mobile Phase 1290-AS Preparation Log.\n17. FM-QC-237: Mobile Phase 1290-CL Preparation Log.\n18. FM-QC-239: Standard Solution 1290-AS Preparation Log.\n19. ES-001: Material, Destruction and Waste Management Procedure.\n20. ES-005: Usage of Personal Protective Equipment (PPE).\n21. QC-029: Gowning Procedure for QC/ARD Laboratory Entry.\n22. P_CQCM-0231: Control of Laboratory Reagents, Solutions and Expiration dating.\n23. QC-016: Usage, Handling and Qualification of Reference Standards.\n24. QC-067: General Laboratory Practices in QC/ARD.\n25. QC-033: Operation Maintenance Cleaning and Calibration of Weigh Balances in the QC/ARD Laboratory.\n26. QC-084: Operation and Calibration of Sartorius MSA6.6s Balance.\n27. FM-QC-246: Standard Solution 1290-AL Preparation Log.\n28. FM-QC-247: Standard Solution 1291-AS Preparation Log.\n29. FM-QC-248: Standard Solution 1291-AL Preparation Log.\n30. FM-QC-249: Standard Solution 1291-CL Preparation Log.\n31. FM-QC-250: Mobile Phase 1291-AS Preparation Log.\n32. FM-QC-251: Mobile Phase 1291-CL Preparation Log.\n33. FM-QC-015: Incoming Reference Standards Logbook.\n34. FM-QC-016: Reference Standards Monthly review Log.\n35. FM-QC-252: Diluent 1291-AS Preparation Log.'),(80,'QC-016C','USAGE, HANDLING AND QUALIFICATION OF REFERENCE STANDARDS','To describe the procedures for acquiring, storing, handling, using, drying, qualifying, labelling, and distributing Reference Standards.\n---\nThis SOP applies to the receipt, usage, handling, and qualification of reference standard material within the QC/AR&D department at Amneal Ireland.\n---\n1. Reference standards must be logged in immediately upon receipt and stored appropriately.\n2. Reference standards must be used before their expiration date.\n3. In-house reference standards are to be used on an \"as is\" basis.\n4. Compendial Reference Standards (CRS) do not require additional qualification testing.\n5. In-house Reference Standards (HRS) must be qualified against a CRS or vendor-supplied certified reference material.\n---\n1. QC-016: First Issued on 30-Sep-2016.\n2. QC-016A: Updated on 24-Sep-2019 to include labelling and second person check upon receipt of standards.\n3. QC-016B: Updated on 26-May-2020 to include a new section on handling reference standards.\n4. QC-016C: Updated on 05-May-2020 to include instructions for monthly standard review and checks by preparer and reviewer.\n---\n1. All analysts must ensure that the reference standard (primary or secondary) lot used is within its expiry date.\n2. The QC/ARD Manager (or designee) is responsible for maintaining storage facilities for reference standards.\n3. The QC/ARD Manager (or designee) is responsible for ensuring that all analysts follow this procedure.\n4. The QC/ARD Manager (or designee) is responsible for maintaining an up-to-date log of all reference standards within QC/AR&D.','QC-016C Usage, Handling & Qualification of Reference Standards.pdf',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:03:44',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'To describe the procedures for acquiring, storing, handling, using, drying, qualifying, labelling, and distributing Reference Standards.','This SOP applies to the receipt, usage, handling, and qualification of reference standard material within the QC/AR&D department at Amneal Ireland.','1. Reference standards must be logged in immediately upon receipt and stored appropriately.\n2. Reference standards must be used before their expiration date.\n3. In-house reference standards are to be used on an \"as is\" basis.\n4. Compendial Reference Standards (CRS) do not require additional qualification testing.\n5. In-house Reference Standards (HRS) must be qualified against a CRS or vendor-supplied certified reference material.','1. QC/ARD: Quality Control/Analytical Research & Development.\n2. Internal Standard (IS): A Reference Standard used as an internal standard in chromatographic analysis.\n3. Reference Material (RS): A material used as a reference standard for calibration and/or assay purposes.\n4. Primary Reference Standard (PRS): A reference standard certified to conform to specific criteria.\n5. Compendial Reference Standard (CRS): A reference standard certified by recognized suppliers such as USP, BP, Ph. Eur., etc.\n6. In-house Reference Standards (HRS): Reference standards certified by Amneal Ireland QC/ARD.\n7. Active Pharmaceutical Ingredient (API): The biologically active ingredient of a pharmaceutical drug.\n8. Amneal Ireland Reference Standard (AIRS) number: A unique number assigned to reference standards by Amneal Ireland.','1. All analysts must ensure that the reference standard (primary or secondary) lot used is within its expiry date.\n2. The QC/ARD Manager (or designee) is responsible for maintaining storage facilities for reference standards.\n3. The QC/ARD Manager (or designee) is responsible for ensuring that all analysts follow this procedure.\n4. The QC/ARD Manager (or designee) is responsible for maintaining an up-to-date log of all reference standards within QC/AR&D.','1. QC-016: First Issued on 30-Sep-2016.\n2. QC-016A: Updated on 24-Sep-2019 to include labelling and second person check upon receipt of standards.\n3. QC-016B: Updated on 26-May-2020 to include a new section on handling reference standards.\n4. QC-016C: Updated on 05-May-2020 to include instructions for monthly standard review and checks by preparer and reviewer.','QC-016B','1. FM-QC-015: Incoming Reference Standards Log.\n2. FM-QC-016: Reference Standard Monthly Review Log.\n3. FM-QC-017: Reference Standard Report form.\n4. QC-015: The Receipt, Preparation, Storage, Labelling and Expiration of Standards, Reagents and Solvents.\n5. Eudralex Chapter 6, Quality Control.\n6. British Pharmacopoeia (BP).\n7. European Pharmacopoeia (Ph. Eur.).\n8. United States Pharmacopeia (USP).\n9. National Institute of Science and Technology (NIST).'),(81,'QC-017A','OPERATION AND MAINTENANCE OF VWR USC 300T/1700T/2600T ULTRASONIC CLEANING BATHS','To define the procedure for the operation and routine maintenance of the VWR USC 300T, 1700T, and 2600T ultrasonic baths.\n---\nThis procedure applies to the Quality Control department at Amneal Ireland.\n---\n1. Unplug the ultrasonic bath before filling or emptying the tank.\n2. Use only water-based cleaning solutions.\n3. Do not operate the ultrasonic bath dry.\n4. Set the timer for sonication.\n5. Degas HPLC solutions by sonication.\n6. Perform monthly maintenance by emptying and refilling the tank.\n---\nQC-017: 30-Sep-2016 - First Issued\nQC-017A: 24-Apr-2020 - Updated SOP to new format, removed reference to Appendix, updated degassing method, and changed monthly water replacement.\n---\n1. All QC/ARD personnel must follow the procedure correctly.\n2. The Laboratory Manager must ensure adherence to the procedure.\n3. Report any equipment problems to the Laboratory Manager.\n4. Ensure all users are trained on the current SOP revision.','QC-017AOperation & Maintenance of the Ultrasonic Cleaning Baths.pdf',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:03:44',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'To define the procedure for the operation and routine maintenance of the VWR USC 300T, 1700T, and 2600T ultrasonic baths.','This procedure applies to the Quality Control department at Amneal Ireland.','1. Unplug the ultrasonic bath before filling or emptying the tank.\n2. Use only water-based cleaning solutions.\n3. Do not operate the ultrasonic bath dry.\n4. Set the timer for sonication.\n5. Degas HPLC solutions by sonication.\n6. Perform monthly maintenance by emptying and refilling the tank.','SOP: Standard Operating Procedure\nHPLC: High Performance Liquid Chromatography\nQC/ARD: Quality Control/ Analytical Research and Development\nAmneal Ireland: Amneal Ireland Limited Cahir Road, Cashel, Co. Tipperary, Ireland.','1. All QC/ARD personnel must follow the procedure correctly.\n2. The Laboratory Manager must ensure adherence to the procedure.\n3. Report any equipment problems to the Laboratory Manager.\n4. Ensure all users are trained on the current SOP revision.','QC-017: 30-Sep-2016 - First Issued\nQC-017A: 24-Apr-2020 - Updated SOP to new format, removed reference to Appendix, updated degassing method, and changed monthly water replacement.','QC-017','FM-QC-018: Ultrasonic Bath Instrument Maintenance Logbook'),(82,'QC-018B','OPERATION, QUALIFICATION AND MAINTENANCE OF THE BINDER DRYING OVENS','To define the procedure for the operation, qualification, and maintenance of the Binder vacuum ovens.\n---\nThis SOP applies to all personnel operating the Binder drying ovens at Amneal Ireland.\n---\n1. Use thermal gloves or tongs for sample transfer.\n2. Check the safety device operation.\n3. Set the safety device response.\n4. Operate the oven using the control panel.\n5. Perform qualification and maintenance as per schedule.\n6. Record all samples in the usage logbook.\n---\nQC-018: 30-Sep-2016 - First Issued\nQC-018A: 17-Sep-2019 - Updated SOP to new logo and removed reference to Appendix.\nQC-018B: 15-Oct-2020 - Removed reference to VD 23, updated vacuum instructions, and made grammatical amendments.\n---\n1. All QC/ARD personnel must follow the procedure.\n2. The Laboratory Manager ensures adherence to the procedure.\n3. Report any equipment problems to the Laboratory Manager.\n4. Ensure all users are trained on the current SOP revision.','QC-018B Operation Qualification & Maintenance of Binder Drying Ovens.pdf',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:03:44',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'To define the procedure for the operation, qualification, and maintenance of the Binder vacuum ovens.','This SOP applies to all personnel operating the Binder drying ovens at Amneal Ireland.','1. Use thermal gloves or tongs for sample transfer.\n2. Check the safety device operation.\n3. Set the safety device response.\n4. Operate the oven using the control panel.\n5. Perform qualification and maintenance as per schedule.\n6. Record all samples in the usage logbook.','LED: light emitting diode\nAmneal Ireland: Amneal Ireland Limited Cahir Road, Cashel, Co. Tipperary, Ireland.','1. All QC/ARD personnel must follow the procedure.\n2. The Laboratory Manager ensures adherence to the procedure.\n3. Report any equipment problems to the Laboratory Manager.\n4. Ensure all users are trained on the current SOP revision.','QC-018: 30-Sep-2016 - First Issued\nQC-018A: 17-Sep-2019 - Updated SOP to new logo and removed reference to Appendix.\nQC-018B: 15-Oct-2020 - Removed reference to VD 23, updated vacuum instructions, and made grammatical amendments.','QC-018A','FM-QC-019: Binder Oven Usage Logbook\nBinder APT.line[TM] VD Vacuum Drying Oven Operating Manual'),(83,'QC-019C','INTEGRATION OF CHROMATOGRAMS IN THE QC/ARD LABORATORY','To provide a systematic approach to peak identification and integration for chromatograms.\n---\nThis procedure is applicable for all chromatograms generated during analysis performed by QC/ARD, Amneal Ireland.\n---\n1. Peak marking based on RT and RRT.\n2. Peak marking based on Blank/Placebo.\n3. Identification of Peak by Spike Solution.\n4. Procedure for Integration of Peaks in a Chromatogram.\n5. General Procedure for integration parameters.\n6. Manual integration requires approval from the Laboratory Manager.\n---\nQC-019: 03-Oct-2016 - First Issued.\nQC-019A: 02-Oct-2019 - Updated SOP to new format, added definitions, and revised integration procedures.\nQC-019B: 08-Nov-2019 - Corrected spelling errors and included diagrams.\nQC-019C: 17-Nov-2021 - Updated manual integration approval process.\n---\n1. Laboratory personnel shall comply with the requirements of this procedure.\n2. Laboratory personnel must ensure they are trained to the current version.\n3. Laboratory Manager or designee ensures adherence to the procedure.\n4. Laboratory Manager or designee ensures all personnel are appropriately trained.','QC-019C Integration of Chromatograms in the QC-ARD Laboratory.pdf',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:03:44',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'To provide a systematic approach to peak identification and integration for chromatograms.','This procedure is applicable for all chromatograms generated during analysis performed by QC/ARD, Amneal Ireland.','1. Peak marking based on RT and RRT.\n2. Peak marking based on Blank/Placebo.\n3. Identification of Peak by Spike Solution.\n4. Procedure for Integration of Peaks in a Chromatogram.\n5. General Procedure for integration parameters.\n6. Manual integration requires approval from the Laboratory Manager.','Chromatogram: Graphical representation of detector response vs time.\nPeak: Portion of chromatographic recording when a component is eluted.\nIntegration: Process of calculating peak areas.\nBaseline: Line representing detector signal when only mobile phase is passing.\nBaseline noise: Irregular variations in the baseline.\nValley: Lowest point between two unresolved peaks.\nParent Peak: Larger of a pair of partially resolved peaks.\nRider Peak: Smaller of a pair of partially resolved peaks.\nResolved Peak: Peak with resolution ≥ 2.0.\nPartially resolved peak: Peak with resolution < 2.0.\nPeak separation: Deriving areas of partially resolved peaks.\nPeak Measurement: Integration involving peak start, apex, and end.\nPeak Area: Area under the curve.\nRetention time (RT): Time for elution of a component.\nRelative retention time (RRT): Ratio of RT of component to reference component.\nDrift and Hump: Baseline shift due to mobile phase or instrumental factors.\nKnown peak: Peak with known origin.\nUnknown peak: Peak with unknown origin.\nPlacebo: Pharmaceutical preparation without active ingredient.\nBlank: Diluent/solvent used for injection.\nPlacebo peak: Peak from placebo portion.\nBlank peak: Peak from blank solution.\nHighest unknown peak: Largest unknown peak.\nSystem suitability: Ensures chromatographic system performance.\nSignal-to-noise ratio: Determines sensitivity of the method.\nQC/ARD: Quality Control/Analytical Research and Development.\nAmneal Ireland: Amneal Ireland Limited, Cahir Road, Cashel, Co. Tipperary, Ireland.\nLimit of Quantitation (LOQ): Lowest quantifiable concentration.\nLimit of Detection (LOD): Lowest detectable concentration.\nDisregard Limit: Peaks below this limit are disregarded.\nScientifically correct integration: Integration visually correct at minimum zoom level.','1. Laboratory personnel shall comply with the requirements of this procedure.\n2. Laboratory personnel must ensure they are trained to the current version.\n3. Laboratory Manager or designee ensures adherence to the procedure.\n4. Laboratory Manager or designee ensures all personnel are appropriately trained.','QC-019: 03-Oct-2016 - First Issued.\nQC-019A: 02-Oct-2019 - Updated SOP to new format, added definitions, and revised integration procedures.\nQC-019B: 08-Nov-2019 - Corrected spelling errors and included diagrams.\nQC-019C: 17-Nov-2021 - Updated manual integration approval process.','QC-019B','USP\nEDQM- Helpdesk - 04- European Pharmacopoeia & International Harmonisation'),(84,'QC-020H','EVALUATION OF SYSTEM SUITABILITY DATA FOR HPLC, GC AND UV-VIS APPLICATIONS','To provide general procedures for the conduct of HPLC, GC, and UV-Vis analysis and describe the process for evaluating system suitability data.\n---\nThis SOP applies to personnel in the QC/ARD laboratory at Amneal Ireland and is supplementary to analytical test methods.\n---\n1. General requirements for system suitability.\n2. Data acquisition and integration procedures.\n3. System suitability for HPLC, GC, and UV-Vis.\n4. Handling system suitability failures.\n5. Chromatographic adjustments to achieve system suitability.\n---\nQC-020: 30-Sep-2016 - First Issued.\nQC-020A: 27-Jun-2018 - Updated definitions and procedures.\nQC-020B: 07-Aug-2018 - Added new definitions and instructions.\nQC-020C: 20-Jun-2019 - Updated title, definitions, and procedures.\nQC-020D: 13-Aug-2020 - Updated diluent injection instructions.\nQC-020E: 25-Sep-2020 - Updated handling of extraneous peaks.\nQC-020F: 02-Feb-2022 - Updated flowchart and references.\nQC-020G: 15-Jun-2022 - Updated standard injection sequence and system suitability procedures.\nQC-020H: 13-Dec-2022 - Updated standard correlation calculation and bracketing standard criteria.\n---\n1. QC/ARD personnel must follow this procedure.\n2. QC/ARD personnel must ensure they are trained on the current revision.\n3. QC/ARD Manager (or designee) ensures adherence to the procedure.','QC-020H Evaluation of SS Data for HPLC, GC & UV-VIS App.pdf',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:03:44',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'To provide general procedures for the conduct of HPLC, GC, and UV-Vis analysis and describe the process for evaluating system suitability data.','This SOP applies to personnel in the QC/ARD laboratory at Amneal Ireland and is supplementary to analytical test methods.','1. General requirements for system suitability.\n2. Data acquisition and integration procedures.\n3. System suitability for HPLC, GC, and UV-Vis.\n4. Handling system suitability failures.\n5. Chromatographic adjustments to achieve system suitability.','HPLC: High Performance Liquid Chromatography.\nGC: Gas Chromatography.\nUV-Vis: Ultra-Violet-Visible.\nIdeal Chromatography: Meets predefined system suitability requirements.\nPoor Chromatography: Identified by symptoms like noisy baseline, shift in retention time, or asymmetric peaks.\nNMT: Not More Than.\nNLT: Not Less Than.\nStandard: Reference standard solution used for system suitability and calibration.\nSystem Suitability: Tests to verify analytical system performance.\nRelative Retention Time (RRT): Retention time of a component relative to a reference peak.\nCapacity Factor (k’): Measure of peak location relative to void volume.\nResolution (R): Measure of separation between two adjacent peaks.\nTailing factor (T): Measure of peak symmetry.\nRelative Standard Deviation (RSD): Measure of reproducibility.\nTheoretical Plates/Column Efficiency: Measure of column performance.\nAmneal Ireland: Amneal Ireland Limited, Cahir Road, Cashel, Co. Tipperary, Ireland.\nAPI: Active Pharmaceutical Ingredient.\nIncident: Unexpected event during laboratory operations.\nApproved Document: Data entry documents approved for recording analytical method execution.','1. QC/ARD personnel must follow this procedure.\n2. QC/ARD personnel must ensure they are trained on the current revision.\n3. QC/ARD Manager (or designee) ensures adherence to the procedure.','QC-020: 30-Sep-2016 - First Issued.\nQC-020A: 27-Jun-2018 - Updated definitions and procedures.\nQC-020B: 07-Aug-2018 - Added new definitions and instructions.\nQC-020C: 20-Jun-2019 - Updated title, definitions, and procedures.\nQC-020D: 13-Aug-2020 - Updated diluent injection instructions.\nQC-020E: 25-Sep-2020 - Updated handling of extraneous peaks.\nQC-020F: 02-Feb-2022 - Updated flowchart and references.\nQC-020G: 15-Jun-2022 - Updated standard injection sequence and system suitability procedures.\nQC-020H: 13-Dec-2022 - Updated standard correlation calculation and bracketing standard criteria.','QC-020G','SOP QC-019: Integration of chromatograms in the QC/ARD Laboratories.\nSOP QC-012: Chromatographic Column Management.\nUnited States Pharmacopeia.\nP_CQCM-1026: Evaluation of Chromatographic and System Suitability Data for HPLC, UPLC, and GC Applications.\nSOP QM-010: Investigation System.\nFM-QC-008: Column receipt and usage logbook.\nSOP QC-086: Handling of Laboratory Incident in the QC/ARD and Microbiology Laboratories.\nSOP QC-001: Investigation of Out of Specification (OOS) Laboratory Results.\nFM-QC-224: Laboratory Incident Report.\nSOP QC-085: Investigation of Atypical Results in the QC Laboratory.\nGQS_0038: Investigation of Unexpected Peaks in Chromatographic Analysis.'),(85,'QC-021B','OPERATION OF EMPOWER SOFTWARE','To provide a systematic approach for the routine operation of Empower Software.\n---\nThis procedure applies to the Quality Control and Analytical Research & Development (QC/ARD) Laboratory at Amneal, Ireland.\n---\nTo provide a systematic approach for the routine operation of Empower Software.\n---\nRevision: QC-021, Date: 30-Sep-2016, CCF No.: --, Reason: First Issued\nRevision: QC-021A, Date: 17-May-2019, CCF No.: AI-CC-18-140 AI-CC-19-010, Reason: Header: New Amneal logo added. New Points added: 5.3.5 Creating an Instrument Method (IM) 5.3.5.8 Instrument Methods shall be created by a “Superuser”. The Superuser should print and sign / date the created Instrument Method and pass to the Laboratory Manger or designee for review. 5.3.5.9 Once the Instrument Method is reviewed and signed / dated by the Laboratory Manger or designee the Instrument Method should be locked by the Superuser from “Chemist” user group. The reviewed Instrument should be stored in a designated folder in the QC/ARD Laboratory. 5.3.5.10 Once locked the Instrument Method can be used for routine use. Note: Instrument methods for Headspace Gas Chromatography cannot be locked as the number of vials require updating for each sample set. Instrument methods for Headspace Gas Chromatography will be printed by the analysts and submitted as part of the chromatographic data pack for review. The instrument method will be reviewed by the data reviewer during the review process. 5.3.6: Creating a Method Set 5.3.6.7 Method Sets shall be created by the “Super User”. The Superuser should print and sign/date the created Method Set and pass to the Laboratory Manger or designee for review. 5.3.6.8 Once the Method Set is reviewed and signed / dated by the Laboratory Manger or designee the Method Set should be locked by a Superuser from “Chemist” user group. The reviewed Method Set should be stored in a designated folder in the QC/ARD Laboratory. 5.3.6.9 Once locked the Method Set can be used for routine use. 5.3.7 Creating Report Method 5.3.7.1 Report Methods shall be created for each analytical procedure in the QC/ARD Laboratory. Report Methods may be created by a Superuser or a Chemist. The Superuser or Chemist should print the created Report Method and pass to the Laboratory Manger or designee for review. 5.3.7.2 Report Methods shall include the following • Sample Set • Processing Method • Component Summary Report • Chromatogram of all injections in the relevant Sample Set A separate report Method should be created for System Suitability. Report Methods must contain all critical information as per the relevant analytical procedure 5.3.7.3 Once the Report Method is reviewed by the Laboratory Manger or designee the Report Methods should be locked by a Superuser from the “Chemist” group. 5.3.7.4 Once locked Report Methods can be used for routine use in the QC/ARD laboratory. Correct typographical error in numbering for section 5.1.1\nRevision: QC-021B, Date: 2020-01-01, CCF No.: AI-CC-19-080, Reason: Section 6.0 updated to reflect new SOP Title for SOP QC-020\n---\nThe QC/ARD personnel are responsible for complying with the requirements of this procedure.\nLaboratory manager or designee shall be responsible to ensure that the steps outlined in this procedure are followed.\nLaboratory manager or designee must ensure that all personnel performing the steps outlined in this procedure are appropriately trained.','QC-021B Operation of Empower Software.pdf',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:03:44',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'To provide a systematic approach for the routine operation of Empower Software.','This procedure applies to the Quality Control and Analytical Research & Development (QC/ARD) Laboratory at Amneal, Ireland.','To provide a systematic approach for the routine operation of Empower Software.','Amneal Ireland: Amneal Ireland Limited Cahir Road, Cashel, Co. Tipperary, Ireland.\nProject: A user defined collection of data including but not limited to methods, results, view filters, custom fields and raw data.\nMethod: An instruction to Empower to perform a task.\nInstrument Method: Instructions to control a chromatographic instrument and collect data.\nProcessing Method: Instructions including but not limited to the following actions: identify peaks, integrate, calculate results, perform system suitability.\nReport Method: Instructions specifying the content and format of chromatographic reports including but not limited to chromatograms, calibration curves, numerical data.\nMethod Set: Collection of methods that must contain the instrument method. May also contain processing method, report method and export method.\nSample Set Method: A set of instructions that defines what samples will be run and how. Information includes but is not limited to vial position, sample name, injection volume.\nSample Set: A set of data acquired after running a sample set method.\nResult Set: A bound set of results generated from processing selected sample sets.','The QC/ARD personnel are responsible for complying with the requirements of this procedure.\nLaboratory manager or designee shall be responsible to ensure that the steps outlined in this procedure are followed.\nLaboratory manager or designee must ensure that all personnel performing the steps outlined in this procedure are appropriately trained.','Revision: QC-021, Date: 30-Sep-2016, CCF No.: --, Reason: First Issued\nRevision: QC-021A, Date: 17-May-2019, CCF No.: AI-CC-18-140 AI-CC-19-010, Reason: Header: New Amneal logo added. New Points added: 5.3.5 Creating an Instrument Method (IM) 5.3.5.8 Instrument Methods shall be created by a “Superuser”. The Superuser should print and sign / date the created Instrument Method and pass to the Laboratory Manger or designee for review. 5.3.5.9 Once the Instrument Method is reviewed and signed / dated by the Laboratory Manger or designee the Instrument Method should be locked by the Superuser from “Chemist” user group. The reviewed Instrument should be stored in a designated folder in the QC/ARD Laboratory. 5.3.5.10 Once locked the Instrument Method can be used for routine use. Note: Instrument methods for Headspace Gas Chromatography cannot be locked as the number of vials require updating for each sample set. Instrument methods for Headspace Gas Chromatography will be printed by the analysts and submitted as part of the chromatographic data pack for review. The instrument method will be reviewed by the data reviewer during the review process. 5.3.6: Creating a Method Set 5.3.6.7 Method Sets shall be created by the “Super User”. The Superuser should print and sign/date the created Method Set and pass to the Laboratory Manger or designee for review. 5.3.6.8 Once the Method Set is reviewed and signed / dated by the Laboratory Manger or designee the Method Set should be locked by a Superuser from “Chemist” user group. The reviewed Method Set should be stored in a designated folder in the QC/ARD Laboratory. 5.3.6.9 Once locked the Method Set can be used for routine use. 5.3.7 Creating Report Method 5.3.7.1 Report Methods shall be created for each analytical procedure in the QC/ARD Laboratory. Report Methods may be created by a Superuser or a Chemist. The Superuser or Chemist should print the created Report Method and pass to the Laboratory Manger or designee for review. 5.3.7.2 Report Methods shall include the following • Sample Set • Processing Method • Component Summary Report • Chromatogram of all injections in the relevant Sample Set A separate report Method should be created for System Suitability. Report Methods must contain all critical information as per the relevant analytical procedure 5.3.7.3 Once the Report Method is reviewed by the Laboratory Manger or designee the Report Methods should be locked by a Superuser from the “Chemist” group. 5.3.7.4 Once locked Report Methods can be used for routine use in the QC/ARD laboratory. Correct typographical error in numbering for section 5.1.1\nRevision: QC-021B, Date: 2020-01-01, CCF No.: AI-CC-19-080, Reason: Section 6.0 updated to reflect new SOP Title for SOP QC-020','QC-021A','SOP: QC-019 Integration of Chromatograms in the QC/ARD Laboratory\nSOP: QC-020 Evaluation of System Suitability Data for HPLC, GC and UV-Vis Applications\nSOP: QC-025 Operation and Maintenance of HPLC System\nSOP: QC-030 Operation and Maintenance of GC System'),(86,'QC-022E','CONTROL OF LABORATORY INSTRUMENTS','To describe the receipt, labelling, qualification, maintenance, re-qualification, re-validation, calibration and repair of instruments/equipment in the Quality Control/Analytical R&D (QC/ARD) and Microbiology Laboratory.\n---\nThis procedure applies to all instruments/equipment in the QC/ARD Laboratories.\n---\nTo describe the receipt, labelling, qualification, maintenance, re-qualification, re-validation, calibration and repair of instruments/equipment in the Quality Control/Analytical R&D (QC/ARD) and Microbiology Laboratory.\n---\nRevision: QC-022, Date: 03-Oct-2016, CCF No.: --, Reason: First issued.\nRevision: QC-022A, Date: 29-Mar-2018, CCF No.: AI-CC-18-014, Reason: Added equipment, re-qualification and re-validation to the Purpose section 1.1. Updated section 2.1 to include equipment. Minor grammatical corrections to section 3. Added responsibilities in section 3 for the Laboratory Manager or designee to ensure all activities are documented as per SOP QM-004, manage spare parts ordering, ensure all contractors meet SOP QA-002 (Contract Service Provider Management). Added responsibilities for persons performing work to adhere to safety signs, wear correct PPE, avoid hot surfaces, have adequate lighting, electrical shocks etc. Added acronyms PM, QC/ARD, SOP, GMP, COTS, SDS, QM, QA, IT, VMP, NIST, NSAI, and NPL to Definitions section 4. Section 4.2 has changed definition to “IQ: Installation Qualification: The documented verification that the facilities, systems, instruments and equipment as installed or modified, comply with the approved design and the manufacturer’s recommendations.” to align with VA-002. Section 4.3 has changed definition to “OQ: Operational Qualification: The documented verification that the facilities, systems, instruments and equipment as installed or modified, perform as intended throughout the anticipated operating ranges.” To align with VA-002. Added definition for Re-validation to Section 4.6. Section 5.1 Added Equipment for clarification. Section 5.1 Added “New instruments shall be assessed and introduced as per QM-013, “Change Control System” if applicable”. Section 5.1 Added “Any instrument that exists on site but has not been previously qualified shall be assessed prior to qualification of this instrument.” Section 5.1.6, responsibility changed to QC/ARD. Added “Record IQ as per VA-002, Appendix IV, “Protocol template for Installation Qualification (IQ).” To Section 5.2.4. Removed reference to presumed instruments in Section 5.2.4. Added “Any re-qualification or re-calibration activities required of the instrument will be managed under the associated Change Control as per this procedure” to Section 5.2.9. Added clarification on the instruments that require qualification following a move to Section 5.2.9. Section 5.5 has been changed from “Instrument Calibration and Preventative Maintenance” to “Instrument Calibration”. Sections 5.5 and 5.5.4 have been amended to reference section 5.4 for categorisation, and SOP QM-007 only for calibration. Section 5.5.2 has been moved to section 5.6.1. Section 5.5.3 is removed as already stated in 3.5. Section 5.5.5 is now covered in section 5.6.10. Section 5.5.6 is re-worded and moved to 5.6.14. Section 5.5.7 is moved to 5.6.11. Section 5.5.8 referencing SOP QM-007 (Calibration Policy) is removed as this SOP does not cover PMs. Section 5.6 amended from ‘Repair of Instruments’ to ‘Instrument PM’ (‘Repair of Instruments’ is now section 5.9). Section 5.6 now covers purpose of PM, forms to be used for annual and monthly PM schedules, reference instruments used, persons qualified to perform PMs, instrument classification, recording and documentation storage, use of labels etc. New section 5.7 added; Maintenance Schedule. New section 5.8 added; Periodic Re-qualification /Re-validation. References expanded to Preventative Maintenance Annual Schedule (FM-QC-123), Preventative Maintenance Monthly Schedule (FM-QC-124), Instrument PM Record – Category A Instruments (FM-QC-125), QM-004, Good Documentation Practices, QA-002, Contract Service Provider Management, QM-010, Investigation System, MF-008, Labelling of Material, Product, Room and Equipment, FM-QM-020, Calibration label, FM-MF-012, Equipment Out of Service/ON HOLD’ label. Update of Appendix II (Instrument Categorisation (FM-QC-027)) to include new instrumentation. Appendix VI and VII added as templates for annual and monthly PM schedules. Appendix VIII added (Instrument PM Record – Category A Instrument). Appendix II updated to include other instrument types. Editorial changes.\nRevision: QC-022B, Date: 18-Sep-2018, CCF No.: AI-CC-18-064, AI-CC-18-097, Reason: Section 5.1.2; replaced ‘Out of Use’ label FM-QC-026 with ‘Out of Use’ label FM-QM-112 (SOP QM-007 Calibration Policy). Section 5.2.13; PM label FM-QC-028 replaced by PM label FM-MF-040, SOP MF-008 Labelling of Material, Product, Room and Equipment. Section 5.6.2 Appendix IV amended to Appendix VI and Appendix V amended to VII to correct typographical errors. Section 5.6.7 Appendix VI amended to Appendix VIII to correct typographical error. Section 5.6.12; replaced ‘Out of Use’ label FM-MF-012 with ‘Out of Use’ label FM-QM-112 (SOP QM-007 Calibration Policy). Section 5.6.13; replaced ‘Equipment Out of Service’/On Hold’ label with ‘Out of Use’ label FM-QM-112, SOP QM-007, Calibration Policy. Changed PM status label from FM-QC-028 to FM-MF-040. Section 5.9.3; replaced ‘Out of Use’ label FM-QC-026 with ‘Out of Use’ label FM-QM-112, SOP QM-007, Calibration Policy. Removed Appendices I and III as no longer required following above changes (see points 1 and 2). Reference to FM-QM-112 Out of Use label, SOP QM-007 added. Addition of FM-MF-040 (Preventative Maintenance Status label) and FM-QM-112 (Out of Use label) to References section, points 6.18 and 6.19 respectively. General editorial changes. Updated Appendix II to include additional new instruments in QC/ARD.\nRevision: QC-022C, Date: 15-Nov-2018, CCF No.: AI-CC-18-125, Reason: Corrected error in the naming of the change controls listed for revision QC-022B. Amended Appendix VII for typographical errors; Page 2 footer in Appendix VII amended from FM-QC-123 to FM-QC-124. Page 2 heading in Appendix VII amended from Appendix VI to Appendix VII.\nRevision: QC-022D, Date: 08-Feb-2019, CCF No.: AI-CC-18-064, Reason: Update procedure to new template. Update Logo in header. Section 1.1 Include “and Microbiology”. Section 2.1 Change Laboratory to Laboratories. Section 4.13 Include “Micro”. Section 4.23 Include Definition for CSV. Section 5.2 Change Laboratory to Laboratories. Section 5.9.2 Include numbering format for Instrument Repair Requests. Section 5.9.9, Addition of “For Microbiology Equipment all repair activities must be documented in the instrument’s usage logbook”. Section 6.17, Include “SOP QM-007”. Update FM-QC-027 to new form template and put titles of form in body of the form as header is removed. Update FM-QC-027 to include new logo in header. Update FM-QC-027 to include a Hotplate. Remove Appendix numbers throughout the document and replace with form number where applicable. Add new point under section 5.5.2 – “In the event that a planned Calibration activity is unable to be completed within it’s defined Calibration schedule window QC/ARD / QA Val and QA can assess impact, if any, and document decision on instrument PM status thereafter. An “Out of Use” label will be applied to the instrument prior to the calibration activity exceeding it’s defined due date pending the outcome of the assessment. The assessment will be documented and stored with the relevant calibration schedule documentation.” Updated section 5.6.2 to remove requirement to initiate an investigation per QM-010 if a planned preventative maintenance task is completed after the allowable due date. Update section 5.6.2 to include “In the event that a planned preventative maintenance activity is unable to be completed within it’s defined PM schedule window QC/ARD / QA Val and QA to assess impact, if any, and document decision on instrument PM status thereafter. An “Out of Use” label will be applied to the instrument prior to the PM activity exceeding it’s defined PM due date (including tolerance where applicable) pending the outcome of the assessment. The assessment will be documented and stored with the relevant maintenance schedule documentation”. Updated form numbers FM-QC-029, FM-QC-030, FM-QC-123, FM-QC-124 and FM-QC-125 to new template and included new logo in header.\n---\nLaboratory personnel shall comply with the requirements of this procedure.\nLaboratory personnel must ensure that they are trained to the current version of this procedure.\nLaboratory Manager or designee shall be responsible for ensuring that the steps outlined in this procedure are followed.\nThe Laboratory Manager or designee must ensure that all personnel performing the steps outlined in this procedure are appropriately trained.\nThe Laboratory Manager or designee is responsible for establishing and implementing the laboratory instrument calibration and preventive maintenance schedule.\nThe Laboratory Manager or designee shall ensure that all activities are documented as per QM-004 (Good Documentation Practices).\nThe Laboratory Manager or designee shall ensure that all contract maintenance providers meet the requirements of SOP QA-002 (Contract Service Provider Management).\nIt is the responsibility of all persons performing calibrations/PM/re-validation/re-qualification work to adhere to all safety signs, notices and guidelines.','QC-022E Control of Laboratory Instruments.pdf',3,2,'2025-11-17 22:05:45',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,9,NULL,1,NULL,'To describe the receipt, labelling, qualification, maintenance, re-qualification, re-validation, calibration and repair of instruments/equipment in the Quality Control/Analytical R&D (QC/ARD) and Microbiology Laboratory.','This procedure applies to all instruments/equipment in the QC/ARD Laboratories.','To describe the receipt, labelling, qualification, maintenance, re-qualification, re-validation, calibration and repair of instruments/equipment in the Quality Control/Analytical R&D (QC/ARD) and Microbiology Laboratory.','AIQ: Analytical Instrument Qualification.\nIQ: Installation Qualification.\nOQ: Operational Qualification.\nPQ: Performance Qualification.\nRQ: Re-qualification.\nRV: Re-validation.\nPM: Preventive Maintenance.\nCalibration: Set of operations that establish the relationship between values indicated by a measuring instrument and the corresponding values realised by standards.\nAmneal Ireland: Amneal Ireland Limited Cahir Road, Cashel, Co. Tipperary, Ireland.\nSOP: Standard Operating Procedure.\nGMP: Good Manufacturing Practice.\nPPE: Personal Protective Equipment.\nQC/ARD-Micro: Quality Control/ Analytical Research & Development and Micro.\nCOTS: Commercial off the Shelf.\nSDS: Safety Data Sheets.\nQM: Quality Management.\nQA: Quality Assurance.\nIT: Information Technology.\nVMP: Validation Master Plan.\nNIST: National Institute of Standards and Technology.\nNSAI: National Standards Authority of Ireland.\nNPL: National Physics Laboratory.\nCSV: Computer Systems Validation.','Laboratory personnel shall comply with the requirements of this procedure.\nLaboratory personnel must ensure that they are trained to the current version of this procedure.\nLaboratory Manager or designee shall be responsible for ensuring that the steps outlined in this procedure are followed.\nThe Laboratory Manager or designee must ensure that all personnel performing the steps outlined in this procedure are appropriately trained.\nThe Laboratory Manager or designee is responsible for establishing and implementing the laboratory instrument calibration and preventive maintenance schedule.\nThe Laboratory Manager or designee shall ensure that all activities are documented as per QM-004 (Good Documentation Practices).\nThe Laboratory Manager or designee shall ensure that all contract maintenance providers meet the requirements of SOP QA-002 (Contract Service Provider Management).\nIt is the responsibility of all persons performing calibrations/PM/re-validation/re-qualification work to adhere to all safety signs, notices and guidelines.','Revision: QC-022, Date: 03-Oct-2016, CCF No.: --, Reason: First issued.\nRevision: QC-022A, Date: 29-Mar-2018, CCF No.: AI-CC-18-014, Reason: Added equipment, re-qualification and re-validation to the Purpose section 1.1. Updated section 2.1 to include equipment. Minor grammatical corrections to section 3. Added responsibilities in section 3 for the Laboratory Manager or designee to ensure all activities are documented as per SOP QM-004, manage spare parts ordering, ensure all contractors meet SOP QA-002 (Contract Service Provider Management). Added responsibilities for persons performing work to adhere to safety signs, wear correct PPE, avoid hot surfaces, have adequate lighting, electrical shocks etc. Added acronyms PM, QC/ARD, SOP, GMP, COTS, SDS, QM, QA, IT, VMP, NIST, NSAI, and NPL to Definitions section 4. Section 4.2 has changed definition to “IQ: Installation Qualification: The documented verification that the facilities, systems, instruments and equipment as installed or modified, comply with the approved design and the manufacturer’s recommendations.” to align with VA-002. Section 4.3 has changed definition to “OQ: Operational Qualification: The documented verification that the facilities, systems, instruments and equipment as installed or modified, perform as intended throughout the anticipated operating ranges.” To align with VA-002. Added definition for Re-validation to Section 4.6. Section 5.1 Added Equipment for clarification. Section 5.1 Added “New instruments shall be assessed and introduced as per QM-013, “Change Control System” if applicable”. Section 5.1 Added “Any instrument that exists on site but has not been previously qualified shall be assessed prior to qualification of this instrument.